{"title_page": "Kevin Chamberlin", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image      = Kevin Chamberlin (46047741285).jpg\n| imagesize  =\n| caption    = Chamberlin in 2019\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|11|25}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/kevinchamberlin/status/404858406252462080|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1985\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Kevin Chamberlin''' (born November 25, 1963<ref name=officialbio/>) is an American actor. He is known for his theatre roles such as Horton in ''[[Seussical]]'' and Fester in ''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]''. For his theatre work, he received three [[Tony Award]] and three [[Drama Desk Award]] nominations. He also starred as [[Bertram Winkle]] in the [[Disney Channel Original Series]] sitcom ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' from 2011 to 2015. From 2018-2019, he starred as [[Wizard of Oz (character)|The Wizard of Oz]] in [[Wicked (musical)|''Wicked'']] on Broadway.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nChamberlin was born in Baltimore, Maryland,<ref name=officialbio/> and was raised in [[Moorestown, New Jersey]]. In elementary school, he starred as [[Huck Finn]] in the school's production of ''[[The Adventures of Tom Sawyer|Tom Sawyer]]''. After he graduated high school, Chamberlin studied acting at [[Rutgers University]]'s Mason Gross School of Arts in New Brunswick,  Jersey, and graduated with a B.F.A. in acting in 1985.<ref name=play1>Karam, Edward. [http://www.playbill.com/article/lord-chamberlin-kevin-chamberlin-breaks-out-of-character-roles-for-now-com-101387# \"Lord Chamberlin: Kevin Chamberlin Breaks Out of Character Roles--For Now\"] Playbill, December 4, 1999</ref>\nChamberlin has since acted on Broadway, having been nominated for three [[Tony Awards]],<ref>[https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/kevin-chamberlin-72996#awards \"Chamberlin Awards\"] ibdb.com, retrieved November 26, 2017</ref> and has an extensive list of film<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/31738|0/Kevin-Chamberlin/filmography.html \"Chamberlin Filmography\"] tcm.com, retrieved November 26, 2017</ref> and television. According to ''Playbill'', \"Chamberlin moves back and forth in theatre, TV and movies, but 'I kind of get sick of each medium after a while, if I have a bad experience,' he says.\"<ref name=play1/> Chamberlin is openly [[gay]].<ref name=\"wc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/gay/lesbian/news/ARTICLE.php?AID=24016|title=Kevin Chamberlin says uncle - 2203 - Trans News - Windy City Times|work=[[Windy City Times]]|last=Nunn|first=Jerry|date=January 6, 2010|accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edgemedianetwork.com/entertainment/theatre//99917|title=Broadway bear Kevin Chamberlin channels Uncle Fester|website=EDGE Media Network|accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nChamberlin has been nominated for [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk]] and [[Tony Award]]s for ''[[Dirty Blonde (play)|Dirty Blonde]]'' (as Charlie), ''[[Seussical]]'' (as Horton), and ''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]'' (as Uncle Fester). Additional [[Broadway theatre]] credits include ''[[My Favorite Year (musical)|My Favorite Year]]'', ''[[Triumph of Love (musical)|Triumph of Love]]'', ''[[Abe Lincoln in Illinois (play)|Abe Lincoln in Illinois]]'', ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'', ''[[The Ritz (play)|The Ritz]]'' and ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]''.\n\nHe appeared in the 1999 film ''[[Trick (1999 film)|Trick]].'' He also appeared in ''[[Die Hard with a Vengeance]]'' as an enthusiastic [[NYPD]] bomb defusal expert. In ''[[Lucky Number Slevin]]'', he again had a supporting role as a New York police officer. Chamberlin's most recent work includes the role of [[List of characters in Heroes#Aron Malsky|Aron Malsky]] in the [[NBC]] prime-time series ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. He also made an appearance in a ''[[Law and Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' episode titled \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 3)|Redemption]]\" where he played a man named Roger Berry. He was also a guest on the sitcom ''[[Frasier]]'', in season 10 episode 13. Chamberlin previously appeared as [[Uncle Fester]] in the [[Musical theatre|musical]] ''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]'', a role for which he won a Broadway.com Audience Award for Favorite Performance By a Featured Actor In a Broadway Musical.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Kenneth|title=''Addams Family'' Musical Finds a Broadway Home|publisher=[[Playbill]]|date=2009-07-22|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131346-Addams_Family_Musical_Finds_a_Broadway_Home_|accessdate=2009-07-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AhUE96MZ?url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131346-Addams-Family-Musical-Finds-a-Broadway-Home-|archivedate=2012-09-15}}</ref> [[Brad Oscar]] replaced him in the role of Uncle Fester on March 8, 2011.<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147337-Brad-Oscar-Will-Play-Uncle-Fester-in-Addams-Family-Blickenstaff-Grupper-Potter-Join-Cast \"Brad Oscar Will Play Uncle Fester in Addams Family; Blickenstaff, Grupper, Potter Join Cast\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208153952/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147337-Brad-Oscar-Will-Play-Uncle-Fester-in-Addams-Family-Blickenstaff-Grupper-Potter-Join-Cast |date=2011-02-08 }} playbill.com, February 4, 2011</ref>\nChamberlin also starred as Dr. Fusion in ''[[Teen Beach Movie]]'', a [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] starring [[Ross Lynch]], [[Maia Mitchell]], [[Barry Bostwick]], and [[Steve Valentine]] which aired July 19, 2013.\n\nIn 2019, Chamberlain appeared as Mr. Mushnik in the [[Pasadena Playhouse]] production of [[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]] alongside [[George Salazar]], [[Mj Rodriguez]], [[Amber Riley]] and [[Matthew Wilkas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenaplayhouse.org/event/little-shop-of-horrors/|title=Little Shop of Horrors|website=Pasadena Playhouse|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n* ''[[Die Hard with a Vengeance]]'' (1995) \u2013 Charles Weiss\n* ''[[In & Out (film)|In & Out]]'' (1997) \u2013 Carl Mickley\n* ''[[Letters from a Killer]]'' (1998) \u2013 Cutler\n* ''[[Trick (1999 film)|Trick]]'' (1999) \u2013 Perry's Ex\n* ''[[Herman U. S. A.]]'' (2001) \u2013 Wayne\n* ''[[Road to Perdition]]'' (2002) \u2013 Frank the Bouncer\n* ''[[Suspect Zero]]'' (2004) \u2013 Harold Speck\n* ''[[Christmas with the Kranks]]'' (2004) \u2013 Mr. Scanlon\n* ''Loudmouth Soup'' (2005) \u2013 Charlie Baker\n* ''[[Lucky Number Slevin]]'' (2006) \u2013 Marty\n* ''[[The Girl Next Door (2007 film)|The Girl Next Door]]'' (2007) \u2013 Officer Jennings\n* ''[[Taking Woodstock]]'' (2009) \u2013 Jackson Spiers\n* ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' (2011\u20132015) \u2013 Bertram Winkle (main role)\n* ''[[The Possession]]'' (2012) \u2013 Keith\n* ''Lucky Stiff'' (2014) \u2013 Fred Mahew III\n* ''[[Teen Beach Movie]]'' (2013) \u2013 Dr. Fusion\n* ''Internet Famous'' (2016) \u2013 Larry Trambone\n* ''[[Bunk'd]]'' (2016) \u2013 Bertram Winkle (in \"Griff is in the House\")\n* ''[[Grace and Frankie]]'' (2017) \u2013 Frank\n* ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' (2017) \u2013 Gavel Emoji (voice)\n* ''[[A Series of Unfortunate Events (TV series)|A Series of Unfortunate Events]]'' (2018) \u2013 Mr. Lesko (2 episodes)\n* ''Fuga di cervelli'' (with [[Paolo Ruffini (actor)|Paolo Ruffini]]) \u2013 Dr. Johnson\n* ''[[Wonder Park]]'' (2019) \u2013 Uncle Tony (voice)\n* ''[[Team Kaylie]]'' (2019) \u2013 Anton\n* ''[[The Prom (film)|The Prom]]'' (2020) \u2013 Sheldon Saperstein\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Work\n!Award \n!Category\n!Result\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2000\n|rowspan=2|''[[Dirty Blonde (play)|Dirty Blonde]]''\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actor in a Play|Outstanding Actor in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2001\n|rowspan=2|''[[Seussical]]''\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actor in a Musical|Outstanding Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2010\n|rowspan=3|''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]''\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical|Best Featured Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical|Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Outer Critics Circle Award]]\n|Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=officialbio>{{cite web |url=http://www.kevinchamberlin.com/about/ |title=About \u2013 Kevin Chamberlin |publisher=Kevin Chamberlin official website |accessdate=October 26, 2014 |quote=BORN: November 25, 1963 in Baltimore, Maryland, USA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026182333/http://www.kevinchamberlin.com/about/ |archivedate=October 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.kevinchamberlin.com}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{IMDb name|0150255}}\n*[https://soundcloud.com/american-theatre-wing/episode-174 ''Downstage Center'' interview] at the [[American Theatre Wing]], November 2007\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chamberlin, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:People from Moorestown, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Maryland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image      = Kevin Chamberlin (46047741285).jpg\n| imagesize  =\n| caption    = Chamberlin in 2019\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|11|25}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/kevinchamberlin/status/404858406252462080|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1985\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Kevin Chamberlin''' (born November 25, 1963<ref name=officialbio/>) is an American actor. He is known for his theatre roles such as Horton in ''[[Seussical]]'' and Fester in ''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]''. For his theatre work, he received three [[Tony Award]] and three [[Drama Desk Award]] nominations. He also starred as [[Bertram Winkle]] in the [[Disney Channel Original Series]] sitcom ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' from 2011 to 2015. From 2018-2019, he starred as [[Wizard of Oz (character)|The Wizard of Oz]] in [[Wicked (musical)|''Wicked'']] on Broadway.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nChamberlin was born in Baltimore, Maryland,<ref name=officialbio/> and was raised in [[Moorestown, New Jersey]]. In elementary school, he starred as [[Huck Finn]] in the school's production of ''[[The Adventures of Tom Sawyer|Tom Sawyer]]''. After he graduated high school, Chamberlin studied acting at [[Rutgers University]]'s Mason Gross School of Arts in New Brunswick,  Jersey, and graduated with a B.F.A. in acting in 1985.<ref name=play1>Karam, Edward. [http://www.playbill.com/article/lord-chamberlin-kevin-chamberlin-breaks-out-of-character-roles-for-now-com-101387# \"Lord Chamberlin: Kevin Chamberlin Breaks Out of Character Roles--For Now\"] Playbill, December 4, 1999</ref>\nChamberlin has since acted on Broadway, having been nominated for three [[Tony Awards]],<ref>[https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/kevin-chamberlin-72996#awards \"Chamberlin Awards\"] ibdb.com, retrieved November 26, 2017</ref> and has an extensive list of film<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/31738|0/Kevin-Chamberlin/filmography.html \"Chamberlin Filmography\"] tcm.com, retrieved November 26, 2017</ref> and television. According to ''Playbill'', \"Chamberlin moves back and forth in theatre, TV and movies, but 'I kind of get sick of each medium after a while, if I have a bad experience,' he says.\"<ref name=play1/> Chamberlin is openly [[gay]].<ref name=\"wc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/gay/lesbian/news/ARTICLE.php?AID=24016|title=Kevin Chamberlin says uncle - 2203 - Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News - Windy City Times|work=[[Windy City Times]]|last=Nunn|first=Jerry|date=January 6, 2010|accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edgemedianetwork.com/entertainment/theatre//99917|title=Broadway bear Kevin Chamberlin channels Uncle Fester|website=EDGE Media Network|accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nChamberlin has been nominated for [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk]] and [[Tony Award]]s for ''[[Dirty Blonde (play)|Dirty Blonde]]'' (as Charlie), ''[[Seussical]]'' (as Horton), and ''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]'' (as Uncle Fester). Additional [[Broadway theatre]] credits include ''[[My Favorite Year (musical)|My Favorite Year]]'', ''[[Triumph of Love (musical)|Triumph of Love]]'', ''[[Abe Lincoln in Illinois (play)|Abe Lincoln in Illinois]]'', ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'', ''[[The Ritz (play)|The Ritz]]'' and ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]''.\n\nHe appeared in the 1999 film ''[[Trick (1999 film)|Trick]].'' He also appeared in ''[[Die Hard with a Vengeance]]'' as an enthusiastic [[NYPD]] bomb defusal expert. In ''[[Lucky Number Slevin]]'', he again had a supporting role as a New York police officer. Chamberlin's most recent work includes the role of [[List of characters in Heroes#Aron Malsky|Aron Malsky]] in the [[NBC]] prime-time series ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. He also made an appearance in a ''[[Law and Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' episode titled \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 3)|Redemption]]\" where he played a man named Roger Berry. He was also a guest on the sitcom ''[[Frasier]]'', in season 10 episode 13. Chamberlin previously appeared as [[Uncle Fester]] in the [[Musical theatre|musical]] ''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]'', a role for which he won a Broadway.com Audience Award for Favorite Performance By a Featured Actor In a Broadway Musical.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Kenneth|title=''Addams Family'' Musical Finds a Broadway Home|publisher=[[Playbill]]|date=2009-07-22|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131346-Addams_Family_Musical_Finds_a_Broadway_Home_|accessdate=2009-07-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AhUE96MZ?url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131346-Addams-Family-Musical-Finds-a-Broadway-Home-|archivedate=2012-09-15}}</ref> [[Brad Oscar]] replaced him in the role of Uncle Fester on March 8, 2011.<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147337-Brad-Oscar-Will-Play-Uncle-Fester-in-Addams-Family-Blickenstaff-Grupper-Potter-Join-Cast \"Brad Oscar Will Play Uncle Fester in Addams Family; Blickenstaff, Grupper, Potter Join Cast\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208153952/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147337-Brad-Oscar-Will-Play-Uncle-Fester-in-Addams-Family-Blickenstaff-Grupper-Potter-Join-Cast |date=2011-02-08 }} playbill.com, February 4, 2011</ref>\nChamberlin also starred as Dr. Fusion in ''[[Teen Beach Movie]]'', a [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] starring [[Ross Lynch]], [[Maia Mitchell]], [[Barry Bostwick]], and [[Steve Valentine]] which aired July 19, 2013.\n\nIn 2019, Chamberlain appeared as Mr. Mushnik in the [[Pasadena Playhouse]] production of [[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]] alongside [[George Salazar]], [[Mj Rodriguez]], [[Amber Riley]] and [[Matthew Wilkas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenaplayhouse.org/event/little-shop-of-horrors/|title=Little Shop of Horrors|website=Pasadena Playhouse|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n* ''[[Die Hard with a Vengeance]]'' (1995) \u2013 Charles Weiss\n* ''[[In & Out (film)|In & Out]]'' (1997) \u2013 Carl Mickley\n* ''[[Letters from a Killer]]'' (1998) \u2013 Cutler\n* ''[[Trick (1999 film)|Trick]]'' (1999) \u2013 Perry's Ex\n* ''[[Herman U. S. A.]]'' (2001) \u2013 Wayne\n* ''[[Road to Perdition]]'' (2002) \u2013 Frank the Bouncer\n* ''[[Suspect Zero]]'' (2004) \u2013 Harold Speck\n* ''[[Christmas with the Kranks]]'' (2004) \u2013 Mr. Scanlon\n* ''Loudmouth Soup'' (2005) \u2013 Charlie Baker\n* ''[[Lucky Number Slevin]]'' (2006) \u2013 Marty\n* ''[[The Girl Next Door (2007 film)|The Girl Next Door]]'' (2007) \u2013 Officer Jennings\n* ''[[Taking Woodstock]]'' (2009) \u2013 Jackson Spiers\n* ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' (2011\u20132015) \u2013 Bertram Winkle (main role)\n* ''[[The Possession]]'' (2012) \u2013 Keith\n* ''Lucky Stiff'' (2014) \u2013 Fred Mahew III\n* ''[[Teen Beach Movie]]'' (2013) \u2013 Dr. Fusion\n* ''Internet Famous'' (2016) \u2013 Larry Trambone\n* ''[[Bunk'd]]'' (2016) \u2013 Bertram Winkle (in \"Griff is in the House\")\n* ''[[Grace and Frankie]]'' (2017) \u2013 Frank\n* ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' (2017) \u2013 Gavel Emoji (voice)\n* ''[[A Series of Unfortunate Events (TV series)|A Series of Unfortunate Events]]'' (2018) \u2013 Mr. Lesko (2 episodes)\n* ''Fuga di cervelli'' (with [[Paolo Ruffini (actor)|Paolo Ruffini]]) \u2013 Dr. Johnson\n* ''[[Wonder Park]]'' (2019) \u2013 Uncle Tony (voice)\n* ''[[Team Kaylie]]'' (2019) \u2013 Anton\n* ''[[The Prom (film)|The Prom]]'' (2020) \u2013 Sheldon Saperstein\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Work\n!Award \n!Category\n!Result\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2000\n|rowspan=2|''[[Dirty Blonde (play)|Dirty Blonde]]''\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actor in a Play|Outstanding Actor in a Play]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2001\n|rowspan=2|''[[Seussical]]''\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actor in a Musical|Outstanding Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2010\n|rowspan=3|''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]''\n|[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical|Best Featured Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical|Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Outer Critics Circle Award]]\n|Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=officialbio>{{cite web |url=http://www.kevinchamberlin.com/about/ |title=About \u2013 Kevin Chamberlin |publisher=Kevin Chamberlin official website |accessdate=October 26, 2014 |quote=BORN: November 25, 1963 in Baltimore, Maryland, USA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026182333/http://www.kevinchamberlin.com/about/ |archivedate=October 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.kevinchamberlin.com}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{IMDb name|0150255}}\n*[https://soundcloud.com/american-theatre-wing/episode-174 ''Downstage Center'' interview] at the [[American Theatre Wing]], November 2007\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chamberlin, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:People from Moorestown, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Maryland]]\n", "name_user": "72.180.106.170", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Chamberlin"}
{"title_page": "Paul Reinman", "text_new": "{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = PaulReinman1964.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Paul Reinman c. 1964\n| birth_name    = Joseph Paul Reinmann\n| birth_date    = September 2, 1910\n| birth_place   = [[German Empire|Germany]]\n| death_date    = September 27, 1988 (aged 78)\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Naturalized American<br />(immigrated German)\n| area          = Inker\n| alias         = \n| signature     = \n| notable works = \n| awards        = \n}}\n'''Paul J. Reinman'''<ref name=ssdi1 /><ref name=ssdi2 /> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|a\u026a|n|m|\u0259|n}}; born '''Joseph Paul Reinmann''',<ref name=tablet>{{cite web | url = http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/116021/a-find-unlocks-comic-mystery?all=1 | publisher = [[Tablet Magazine|Tabletmag.com]] | title= A Find Unlocks Comics Mystery | first= Gideon | last=Remez | date = November 8, 2012 | accessdate = September 9, 2013 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130613180139/http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/116021/a-find-unlocks-comic-mystery?all=1 | archivedate= June 13, 2013 | url-status=live}}</ref> {{IPA-de|\u02c8\u0281a\u026anman|lang}}; 2 September 1910 \u2013 27 September 1988)<ref name=ssdi1>[https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/VMG6-WMC Paul J. Reinmen], [[Social Security Number]] 127-09-2592, at the [[Social Security Death Index]] via FamilySearch.or. Retrieved March 2, 2013.</ref><ref name=ssdi2>[http://www.genealogybank.com/gbnk/ssdi/doc/ssdi/v1:112EBE0149B22BD7 Paul J. Reinman] at the Social Security Death Index via GenealogyBank.com</ref> was an [[United States of America|American]] [[comic book]] artist best known as one of [[Jack Kirby]]'s frequent inkers during the period comics fans and historians call the [[Silver Age of Comic Books]]. This included  the first issues of ''[[The Incredible Hulk (comic book)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' and ''[[Uncanny X-Men|The X-Men]]''.<!--title at the time Reinman worked on it-->\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and career===\nPaul Reinman was born in [[German Empire|Germany]]<ref name=lam>[http://lambiek.net/artists/r/reinman_paul.htm Paul Reinman] at the [[Lambiek Comiclopedia]]. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912132414/http://www.lambiek.net/artists/r/reinman_paul.htm |date=September 12, 2012 }}.</ref> and raised in [[Worms, Germany#Boroughs of Worms|Pfiffligheim]], a borough of [[Worms, Germany|Worms]], seat of one of the oldest [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] communities. The second of five children, and the eldest son, of real-estate agent and farm-produce broker Bernhard and his wife, he began drawing at age 3. By his early twenties, he was creating pen-and-ink drawings of such subjects as the [[Worms Synagogue|Rashi Synagogue]], which was shortly afterward destroyed by the [[Nazis]]. Emigrating, he arrived in [[New York City]] on June 15, 1934, joining an aunt, Johanna, who had come to the [[United States]] circa 1890, and a cousin, Willi, who had arrived in 1927. Reinman eventually brought his younger brother Friedrich and sister Emmy in 1936; their parents and Willi's brother Ludwig, an artist, in 1937; and his older sister Alice in March 1938. Another younger brother, Hans, remained in Germany, but eventually escaped and made his way to the U.S. in November 1945, and changed his name to John.<ref name=tablet />\n\nReinman married Dora, an immigrant from [[Reichelsheim (Odenwald)|Reichelsheim]], a city near Worms, in September 1938. The couple had a daughter born circa 1944.<ref name=tablet />\n\nIn the 1930s, Reinman entered the field of [[commercial art]] in New York, recalling in 1988,\n\n{{quote|My first job was as assistant to a designer of neon signs. Then the going got tough and I took any kind of job just to make ends meet, and I worked in the check room of an exclusive men's club on New York's East side \u2026 but luckily I had a chance to get back to art and I took a job in a studio of a match factory. Here I did designs of match covers and lettering. A few years later I quit and started to freelance in posters, fashion drawings, and package designs. Then I brushed up on my drawing technique and practiced illustration in many mediums. I succeeded in getting assignments for dry brush drawings for pulp mags, and following this I broke into comic-book cartooning.<ref name=tablet />}}\n\n===Golden Age of Comics===\nThis was at [[MLJ Comics]], the future [[Archie Comics]].<ref name=tablet /> Because credits were not routinely given in the early days of comic books, a comprehensive bibliography of early creators is difficult to ascertain. Reinman's earliest known confirmed work was at [[Timely Comics]], the precursor of [[Marvel Comics]], where he [[penciler|penciled]] and [[inker|inked]] a seven-page story starring the [[superhero]] the Falcon (no relation to [[Falcon (Marvel Comics)|the Marvel superhero introduced in 1969]]) in ''[[Jim Hammond (comics)|The Human Torch]]'' #2 (Fall 1940). His earliest known signed story is the 12-page \"Plague of the Poisoned Jewelry\", starring super-speedster the [[Whizzer (Robert Frank)|Whizzer]], in Timely's ''[[All Winners Comics]]'' #2 (Fall 1941).<ref name=gcd>[http://www.comics.org/credit/name/paul%20reinman/sort/chrono/ Paul Reinman] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]</ref>\n\nAlso during this time, Reinman created or co-created (the writer is unknown) the superhero the Fireball in MLJ's ''[[Pep Comics]]'' #12 (Feb. 1941),<ref>[http://toonopedia.com/fireball.htm Fireball] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6jHCphWFa?url=http://toonopedia.com/fireball.htm Archived] from the original on July 25, 2016.</ref> the first known of many characters and stories he would draw for that company throughout the 1940s period known as the [[Golden Age of Comic Books]]. Reinman drew for such MLJ  titles as ''[[Blue Ribbon Comics]]'', ''Hangman Comics'', ''Jackpot Comics'', ''Shield-Wizard Comics'', ''Top-Notch Comics'', and ''Zip Comics'', on such characters as the [[Black Hood]], the [[Hangman (Archie Comics)|Hangman]], and the [[Wizard (Archie Comics)|Wizard]].<ref name=gcd />\n\nReinman then began a long stint drawing for [[All-American Publications]], one of the companies that later merged into [[DC Comics]]. He became one of the primary artists on the Golden Age [[Green Lantern]] (signing some of many covers and stories '''\"P.R.\"''') before succeeding series creators Ben Flinton and Jon Kozlak on the [[Atom (comics)|Atom]] from 1947 to 1949. In the flagship title ''[[All-American Comics]]'' and in ''[[All-Star Comics]]'', ''[[Comic Cavalcade]]'', ''[[Sensation Comics]]'' and others series, Reinman drew stories featuring those character and others, including [[Starman (DC Comics Golden Age)|Starman]], [[Wildcat (DC Comics)|Wildcat]], and [[Wonder Woman]].<ref name=gcd />\n\nHis sporadic later work for Timely included [[Human Torch (android)|Human Torch]] and [[Sub-Mariner]] stories in ''[[Captain America|Captain America Comics]]'' and elsewhere.  Reinman went on to [[penciler|pencil]] [[horror fiction|horror]], [[science fiction]], [[Bible stories]], war fiction and other genres for Marvel's 1950s predecessor, [[Atlas Comics (1950s)|Atlas Comics]], starting with a seven-page [[horror comics]] story in ''[[Strange Tales]]'' #1 (June 1951).<ref name=gcd />\n\n===Atlas and the Silver Age===\n[[Image:Hulk1.jpg|thumb|''The Incredible Hulk'' #1 (May 1962). Cover art by [[Jack Kirby]] and inker Reinman]]\nComics historian Michael J. Vassallo cites the Atlas [[war-comics]] tale \"Atrocity Story\" in ''Battlefield'' #2 (June 1952) as \"Reinman's finest hour and ... one of the most challenging and intensely illustrated stories in the Atlas war comics line\". Written by [[Hank Chapman]],\n\n{{quote|\"Atrocity Story\" is not really a story at all, but rather a body of exposition in narrative form conveying information.... Chapman starts off with screaming headlines of brutal Communist atrocities done to U.S. and U.N. troops and unarmed civilians. He then draws comparisons to Nazi atrocities perpetrated by the Third Reich.... Paul Reinman renders this broadcast in newsreel fashion starting off with a magnificent full-page splash depicting a score of inhumanly bound and slaughtered U.S. Marines. The tempo picks up and using smaller and smaller panels, Reinman displays one atrocity after another. The panel-to-panel progression is swift and Reinman's art is crisp and starkly grim with dark shadowing in the inks. Page 5 is a disturbing eight-panel review of the atrocities on the Nazi concentration camps depicting dead camp victims and riveting single panels of hollow-eyed, skeletal survivors.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://timely-atlas-comics.blogspot.com/2013/05/a-history-of-atlas-war-comics-1950-1960.html | first= Michael J. | last=Vassallo | publisher = Timely-Atlas-Comics | date= May 4, 2013 | accessdate = September 9, 2013 | title =A History of Atlas War Comics (1950-1960) | archivedate= August 20, 2013 | url-status =  live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130820053454/http://timely-atlas-comics.blogspot.com/2013/05/a-history-of-atlas-war-comics-1950-1960.html}}</ref>}}\n\nWith the late-1950s return of comics legend [[Jack Kirby]] to [[Atlas Comics (1950s)|Atlas Comics]], on the cusp of it becoming [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], Reinman became a frequent Kirby [[inker]] in such \"[[Atlas Comics (1950s)#Pre-superhero Marvel|pre-superhero Marvel]]\" [[science-fiction]]/[[fantasy]] [[anthologies]] as ''[[Strange Tales]]'' and ''[[Journey into Mystery]]'', as well as on the espionage series ''[[Yellow Claw (comics)|Yellow Claw]]''. After the advent of the company's first superheroes and its evolution into Marvel, Reinman would ink Kirby on numerous landmark books, including ''The Incredible Hulk'' #1 (May 1962), ''[[Uncanny X-Men|The X-Men]]'' <!--title at the time Reinman worked on it--> #1-5 (Sept. 1963 - May 1964), and ''[[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]]'' #2, 3 & 5 (Nov. 1963, Jan. & May 1964).<ref name=gcd />\n\nIn 1965, Reinman left Marvel and with [[Superman]] co-creator [[Jerry Siegel]] created [[The Mighty Crusaders]] for [[Archie Comics]]' short-lived [[superhero]] line. Reinman also worked with Siegel on that company's version of the [[The Shadow|Shadow]], based on the 1930s [[radio]] and [[pulp magazine]] character. The prolific Reinman's other work includes numerous issues of ''Adventures into the Unknown'' and ''[[Forbidden Worlds]]'' for the small [[American Comics Group]] (AGC) in the 1950s and 1960s. He and writer-editor [[Richard E. Hughes]] co-created the spy character John Force in ACG's ''Magic Agent'' #1 (Feb. 1962).<ref name=gcd />\n\nReinman afterward returned to Marvel, where he remained active through at least the mid-1970s, penciling ''[[Ka-Zar (comics)|Ka-Zar]]'' #1 (Jan. 1974) and assisting [[John Romita, Sr.]] on the pencils of ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' #132 (May 1974).<ref name=gcd /> He also worked as a [[colorist]] for the company during this time.<ref name = lam/>\n\n==Other work==\nOutside comic books, Reinman drew the ''[[Tarzan]]'' [[print syndication|syndicated]] [[comic strip]] in 1949 and 1950, and the comic strip ''Merrie Chase'' in 1950 and 1951.<ref>[http://www.bpib.com/comicsproj/biogR1.html Paul Reinman entry], The Comic Strip Project, \"Who's Who of Comic Strip Producers\"\", R-1. [https://www.webcitation.org/5qyYbgF91?url=http://www.bpib.com/comicsproj/ WebCitation archive].</ref>\n\n===Later life===\nReinman's sister Alice and her husband Alex Leopold moved to [[Boca Raton, Florida]], in [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]], and Reinman, following the death of wife Dora in 1967 and his leaving comics in the mid-1970s, settled nearby with his second wife, Celia.<ref name=tablet /> There, Reinman drew courtroom sketches for television-news broadcasts, as well as movie posters and advertising art.<ref name=tablet /> Reinman was living in Palm Beach County at the time of his death.<ref name=ssdi1 /><ref name=ssdi2 />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''[[Alter Ego (magazine)|Alter Ego]]'' #42, November 2004\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | url = http://www.askart.com/askart/r/paul_reinman/paul_reinman.aspx | publisher = Ask Art: The American Artists Bluebook | title= Paul Reinman | archivedate= July 16, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120716182454/http://www.askart.com/askart/r/paul_reinman/paul_reinman.aspx | url-status =live}}\n* Vassallo, Michael J. [http://www.comicartville.com/esotericatlas.htm \"Esoteric Atlas: ''Bible Tales for Young Folk''\"], Comicartville Library, 2002, n.d. [https://www.webcitation.org/5n7q80rdE?url=http://www.comicartville.com/esotericatlas.htm WebCitation archive].\n* WebCitation archive of [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/hillmans26/erbz691.html&date=2009-10-26+00:00:39 \"Bob Hyde's Odyssey of a Tarzan Fanatic, Chapter XIV\"], ''ERBzin-e'' #621\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reinman, Paul}}\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics creators]]\n[[Category:Silver Age comics creators]]\n[[Category:Atlas Comics]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics people]]\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = PaulReinman1964.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Paul Reinman c. 1964\n| birth_name    = Joseph Paul Reinmann\n| birth_date    = September 2, 1910\n| birth_place   = [[German Empire|Germany]]\n| death_date    = September 27, 1988 (aged 78)\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Naturalized American<br />(immigrated German)\n| area          = Inker\n| alias         = \n| signature     = \n| notable works = \n| awards        = \n}}\n'''Paul J. Reinman'''<ref name=ssdi1 /><ref name=ssdi2 /> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|a\u026a|n|m|\u0259|n}}; born '''Joseph Paul Reinmann''',<ref name=tablet>{{cite web | url = http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/116021/a-find-unlocks-comic-mystery?all=1 | publisher = [[Tablet Magazine|Tabletmag.com]] | title= A Find Unlocks Comics Mystery | first= Gideon | last=Remez | date = November 8, 2012 | accessdate = September 9, 2013 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130613180139/http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/116021/a-find-unlocks-comic-mystery?all=1 | archivedate= June 13, 2013 | url-status=live}}</ref> {{IPA-de|\u02c8\u0281a\u026anman|lang}}; 2 September 1910 \u2013 27 September 1988)<ref name=ssdi1>[https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/VMG6-WMC Paul J. Reinmen], [[Social Security Number]] 127-09-2592, at the [[Social Security Death Index]] via FamilySearch.or. Retrieved March 2, 2013.</ref><ref name=ssdi2>[http://www.genealogybank.com/gbnk/ssdi/doc/ssdi/v1:112EBE0149B22BD7 Paul J. Reinman] at the Social Security Death Index via GenealogyBank.com</ref> was an [[United States of America|American]] [[comic book]] artist best known as one of [[Jack Kirby]]'s frequent inkers during the period comics fans and historians call the [[Silver Age of Comic Books]]. This included  the first issues of ''[[The Incredible Hulk (comic book)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' and ''[[Uncanny X-Men|The X-Men]]''.<!--title at the time Reinman worked on it-->\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and career===\nPaul Reinman was born in [[German Empire|Germany]]<ref name=lam>[http://lambiek.net/artists/r/reinman_paul.htm Paul Reinman] at the [[Lambiek Comiclopedia]]. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912132414/http://www.lambiek.net/artists/r/reinman_paul.htm |date=September 12, 2012 }}.</ref> and raised in [[Worms, Germany#Boroughs of Worms|Pfiffligheim]], a borough of [[Worms, Germany|Worms]], seat of one of the oldest [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] communities. The second of five children, and the eldest son, of real-estate agent and farm-produce broker Bernhard and his wife, he began drawing at age 3. By his early twenties, he was creating pen-and-ink drawings of such subjects as the [[Worms Synagogue|Rashi Synagogue]], which was shortly afterward destroyed by the [[Nazis]]. Emigrating, he arrived in [[New York City]] on June 15, 1934, joining an aunt, Johanna, who had come to the [[United States]] circa 1890, and a cousin, Willi, who had arrived in 1927. Reinman eventually brought his younger brother Friedrich and sister Emmy in 1936; their parents and Willi's brother Ludwig, an artist, in 1937; and his older sister Alice in March 1938. Another younger brother, Hans, remained in Germany, but eventually escaped and made his way to the U.S. in November 1945, and changed his name to John.<ref name=tablet />\n\nReinman married Dora, an immigrant from [[Reichelsheim (Odenwald)|Reichelsheim]], a city near Worms, in September 1938. The couple had a daughter born circa 1944.<ref name=tablet />\n\nIn the 1930s, Reinman entered the field of [[commercial art]] in New York, recalling in 1988,\n\n{{quote|My first job was as assistant to a designer of neon signs. Then the going got tough and I took any kind of job just to make ends meet, and I worked in the check room of an exclusive men's club on New York's East side \u2026 but luckily I had a chance to get back to art and I took a job in a studio of a match factory. Here I did designs of match covers and lettering. A few years later I quit and started to freelance in posters, fashion drawings, and package designs. Then I brushed up on my drawing technique and practiced illustration in many mediums. I succeeded in getting assignments for dry brush drawings for pulp mags, and following this I broke into comic-book cartooning.<ref name=tablet />}}\n\n===Golden Age of Comics===\nThis was at [[MLJ Comics]], the future [[Archie Comics]].<ref name=tablet /> Because credits were not routinely given in the early days of comic books, a comprehensive bibliography of early creators is difficult to ascertain. Reinman's earliest known confirmed work was at [[Timely Comics]], the precursor of [[Marvel Comics]], where he [[penciler|penciled]] and [[inker|inked]] a seven-page story starring the [[superhero]] the Falcon (no relation to [[Falcon (Marvel Comics)|the Marvel superhero introduced in 1969]]) in ''[[Jim Hammond (comics)|The Human Torch]]'' #2 (Fall 1940). His earliest known signed story is the 12-page \"Plague of the Poisoned Jewelry\", starring super-speedster the [[Whizzer (Robert Frank)|Whizzer]], in Timely's ''[[All Winners Comics]]'' #2 (Fall 1941).<ref name=gcd>[http://www.comics.org/credit/name/paul%20reinman/sort/chrono/ Paul Reinman] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]</ref>\n\nAlso during this time, Reinman created or co-created (the writer is unknown) the superhero the Fireball in MLJ's ''[[Pep Comics]]'' #12 (Feb. 1941),<ref>[http://toonopedia.com/fireball.htm Fireball] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6jHCphWFa?url=http://toonopedia.com/fireball.htm Archived] from the original on July 25, 2016.</ref> the first known of many characters and stories he would draw for that company throughout the 1940s period known as the [[Golden Age of Comic Books]]. Reinman drew for such MLJ  titles as ''[[Blue Ribbon Comics]]'', ''Hangman Comics'', ''Jackpot Comics'', ''Shield-Wizard Comics'', ''Top-Notch Comics'', and ''Zip Comics'', on such characters as the [[Black Hood]], the [[Hangman (Archie Comics)|Hangman]], and the [[Wizard (Archie Comics)|Wizard]].<ref name=gcd />\n\nReinman then began a long stint drawing for [[All-American Publications]], one of the companies that later merged into [[DC Comics]]. He became one of the primary artists on the Golden Age [[Green Lantern]] (signing some of many covers and stories '''\"P.R.\"''') before succeeding series creators Ben Flinton and Jon Kozlak on the [[Atom (comics)|Atom]] from 1947 to 1949. In the flagship title ''[[All-American Comics]]'' and in ''[[All-Star Comics]]'', ''[[Comic Cavalcade]]'', ''[[Sensation Comics]]'' and others series, Reinman drew stories featuring those character and others, including [[Starman (DC Comics Golden Age)|Starman]], [[Wildcat (comics)|Wildcat]], and [[Wonder Woman]].<ref name=gcd />\n\nHis sporadic later work for Timely included [[Human Torch (android)|Human Torch]] and [[Sub-Mariner]] stories in ''[[Captain America|Captain America Comics]]'' and elsewhere.  Reinman went on to [[penciler|pencil]] [[horror fiction|horror]], [[science fiction]], [[Bible stories]], war fiction and other genres for Marvel's 1950s predecessor, [[Atlas Comics (1950s)|Atlas Comics]], starting with a seven-page [[horror comics]] story in ''[[Strange Tales]]'' #1 (June 1951).<ref name=gcd />\n\n===Atlas and the Silver Age===\n[[Image:Hulk1.jpg|thumb|''The Incredible Hulk'' #1 (May 1962). Cover art by [[Jack Kirby]] and inker Reinman]]\nComics historian Michael J. Vassallo cites the Atlas [[war-comics]] tale \"Atrocity Story\" in ''Battlefield'' #2 (June 1952) as \"Reinman's finest hour and ... one of the most challenging and intensely illustrated stories in the Atlas war comics line\". Written by [[Hank Chapman]],\n\n{{quote|\"Atrocity Story\" is not really a story at all, but rather a body of exposition in narrative form conveying information.... Chapman starts off with screaming headlines of brutal Communist atrocities done to U.S. and U.N. troops and unarmed civilians. He then draws comparisons to Nazi atrocities perpetrated by the Third Reich.... Paul Reinman renders this broadcast in newsreel fashion starting off with a magnificent full-page splash depicting a score of inhumanly bound and slaughtered U.S. Marines. The tempo picks up and using smaller and smaller panels, Reinman displays one atrocity after another. The panel-to-panel progression is swift and Reinman's art is crisp and starkly grim with dark shadowing in the inks. Page 5 is a disturbing eight-panel review of the atrocities on the Nazi concentration camps depicting dead camp victims and riveting single panels of hollow-eyed, skeletal survivors.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://timely-atlas-comics.blogspot.com/2013/05/a-history-of-atlas-war-comics-1950-1960.html | first= Michael J. | last=Vassallo | publisher = Timely-Atlas-Comics | date= May 4, 2013 | accessdate = September 9, 2013 | title =A History of Atlas War Comics (1950-1960) | archivedate= August 20, 2013 | url-status =  live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130820053454/http://timely-atlas-comics.blogspot.com/2013/05/a-history-of-atlas-war-comics-1950-1960.html}}</ref>}}\n\nWith the late-1950s return of comics legend [[Jack Kirby]] to [[Atlas Comics (1950s)|Atlas Comics]], on the cusp of it becoming [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], Reinman became a frequent Kirby [[inker]] in such \"[[Atlas Comics (1950s)#Pre-superhero Marvel|pre-superhero Marvel]]\" [[science-fiction]]/[[fantasy]] [[anthologies]] as ''[[Strange Tales]]'' and ''[[Journey into Mystery]]'', as well as on the espionage series ''[[Yellow Claw (comics)|Yellow Claw]]''. After the advent of the company's first superheroes and its evolution into Marvel, Reinman would ink Kirby on numerous landmark books, including ''The Incredible Hulk'' #1 (May 1962), ''[[Uncanny X-Men|The X-Men]]'' <!--title at the time Reinman worked on it--> #1-5 (Sept. 1963 - May 1964), and ''[[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]]'' #2, 3 & 5 (Nov. 1963, Jan. & May 1964).<ref name=gcd />\n\nIn 1965, Reinman left Marvel and with [[Superman]] co-creator [[Jerry Siegel]] created [[The Mighty Crusaders]] for [[Archie Comics]]' short-lived [[superhero]] line. Reinman also worked with Siegel on that company's version of the [[The Shadow|Shadow]], based on the 1930s [[radio]] and [[pulp magazine]] character. The prolific Reinman's other work includes numerous issues of ''Adventures into the Unknown'' and ''[[Forbidden Worlds]]'' for the small [[American Comics Group]] (AGC) in the 1950s and 1960s. He and writer-editor [[Richard E. Hughes]] co-created the spy character John Force in ACG's ''Magic Agent'' #1 (Feb. 1962).<ref name=gcd />\n\nReinman afterward returned to Marvel, where he remained active through at least the mid-1970s, penciling ''[[Ka-Zar (comics)|Ka-Zar]]'' #1 (Jan. 1974) and assisting [[John Romita, Sr.]] on the pencils of ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' #132 (May 1974).<ref name=gcd /> He also worked as a [[colorist]] for the company during this time.<ref name = lam/>\n\n==Other work==\nOutside comic books, Reinman drew the ''[[Tarzan]]'' [[print syndication|syndicated]] [[comic strip]] in 1949 and 1950, and the comic strip ''Merrie Chase'' in 1950 and 1951.<ref>[http://www.bpib.com/comicsproj/biogR1.html Paul Reinman entry], The Comic Strip Project, \"Who's Who of Comic Strip Producers\"\", R-1. [https://www.webcitation.org/5qyYbgF91?url=http://www.bpib.com/comicsproj/ WebCitation archive].</ref>\n\n===Later life===\nReinman's sister Alice and her husband Alex Leopold moved to [[Boca Raton, Florida]], in [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]], and Reinman, following the death of wife Dora in 1967 and his leaving comics in the mid-1970s, settled nearby with his second wife, Celia.<ref name=tablet /> There, Reinman drew courtroom sketches for television-news broadcasts, as well as movie posters and advertising art.<ref name=tablet /> Reinman was living in Palm Beach County at the time of his death.<ref name=ssdi1 /><ref name=ssdi2 />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''[[Alter Ego (magazine)|Alter Ego]]'' #42, November 2004\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | url = http://www.askart.com/askart/r/paul_reinman/paul_reinman.aspx | publisher = Ask Art: The American Artists Bluebook | title= Paul Reinman | archivedate= July 16, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120716182454/http://www.askart.com/askart/r/paul_reinman/paul_reinman.aspx | url-status =live}}\n* Vassallo, Michael J. [http://www.comicartville.com/esotericatlas.htm \"Esoteric Atlas: ''Bible Tales for Young Folk''\"], Comicartville Library, 2002, n.d. [https://www.webcitation.org/5n7q80rdE?url=http://www.comicartville.com/esotericatlas.htm WebCitation archive].\n* WebCitation archive of [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/hillmans26/erbz691.html&date=2009-10-26+00:00:39 \"Bob Hyde's Odyssey of a Tarzan Fanatic, Chapter XIV\"], ''ERBzin-e'' #621\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reinman, Paul}}\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics creators]]\n[[Category:Silver Age comics creators]]\n[[Category:Atlas Comics]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics people]]\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toWildcat (disambiguation)(link changed toWildcat (DC Comics)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Reinman"}
{"title_page": "Red Tornado (Ma Hunkel)", "text_new": ":''For information on the [[Silver Age of comic books|Silver Age]] Red Tornado, see [[Red Tornado]].''\n{{Infobox comics character <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image= Red Tornado Hunkel.jpg\n|caption=\"Ma\" Hunkel, the Golden Age Red Tornado.  Art by Sheldon Mayer.\n|character_name=Red Tornado\n|real_name=Abigail Mathilda \"Ma\" Hunkel\n|publisher=[[DC Comics]]\n|debut='''(As Ma Hunkel)''':<br> ''All-American Comics'' #3<br>(June 1939)<br>'''(As Red Tornado)''':<br> ''All-American Comics'' #20<br>(November 1940)\n|creators=[[Sheldon Mayer]]\n|alliances=[[Justice Society of America]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Great cook<br>Surprising physical strength       \n}}\n\nThe '''Red Tornado''' is a [[fictional character]], a [[superheroine]] in the [[DC Comics]] [[DC Universe|Universe]], debuting during the [[Golden Age of Comic Books]]. Created by [[Sheldon Mayer]], she [[first appeared]] in her civilian identity as '''Abigail Mathilda''' \"'''Ma'''\" '''Hunkel''' in [[All-American Publications]]' ''[[All-American Comics]]'' #3 (June 1939), and became the Red Tornado in ''All-American Comics'' #20 (Nov. 1940). As the Red Tornado, she was one of the first superhero [[parody|parodies]], as well as one of the first female superheroes (possibly the very first<ref>{{cite book |last=Coogan |first=Peter |date=2006 |title=Superhero: The Secret Origin of a Genre |url=https://books.google.com.au/books/about/Superhero.html?id=vnkrAQAAIAAJ |location=Austin, Texas |publisher=[[MonkeyBrain Books]] |page= |isbn=9781932265187 |author-link=Peter Coogan |access-date=July 4, 2007}}</ref>), and, when occasionally disguised as a man, comics' first cross-dressing heroine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ragnell.blogspot.com/2006/05/mama-thon-red-tornado.html |title=Mama-Thon -- The Red Tornado |author=Ragnell |date=May 11, 2006 |website=Written World |publisher= |access-date=December 1, 2006 |quote=}}</ref> ([[Madame Fatal]], earlier that year, was the first cross-dressing hero.)\n\n==Publication history==\nInitially as simply Ma Hunkel, the Golden Age Red Tornado originated in Sheldon Mayer's semi-autobiographical humor feature ''[[Scribbly the Boy Cartoonist]]'' in ''All-American Comics''.<ref name=Toonopedia>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |title=Scribbly the Boy Cartoonist |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/scribbly.htm |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nWith the skyrocketing popularity of the ''[[Superman]]'' comic in 1938, comic book publishers began featuring their own superhero characters. ''All-American Comics'' responded in 1939 with [[Gary Concord, the Ultra-Man]], and followed in 1940 with [[Green Lantern]] and [[the Atom]]. The superhero trend was so powerful that in the ''Scribbly'' story in issue #20 (Nov 1940), Ma Hunkel became a superhero herself.<ref>{{cite book |last=Coogan |first=Peter |date=2006 |title=Superhero: The Secret Origin of a Genre |pages=26-27 |location=Austin, Texas |publisher=[[MonkeyBrain Books]] |page= |isbn=9781932265187 |author-link=Peter Coogan}}</ref> In the story, Scribbly's little brother and Ma Hunkel's daughter Sisty are kidnapped, and the police are unable to locate them. Scribbly tells Ma about the Green Lantern, and she's inspired to don a costume and fight crime, calling herself the Red Tornado. By issue #23, the Red Tornado was sharing billing with Scribbly, and in #24, Ma's two kids joined the fight against crime, calling themselves \"the Cyclone Twins\".<ref name=\"Goulart\">{{cite book |last1=Goulart |first1=Ron |title=The Encyclopedia of American Comics: From 1897 to the Present |date=1990 |publisher=Facts on File |isbn=0-8160-1852-9 |pages=322-323}}</ref> The series continued for three more years as \"Scribbly & the Red Tornado\".<ref name=Toonopedia/>\n\nThe feature ran through ''All-American Comics'' #59, in 1944,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://users.cvalley.net/canote/tornado.html |title=Justice Society Profile: Red Tornado |last=Canote |first=Terry |date= |website=Terry Canote's Homepage |publisher= |access-date=December 1, 2006 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206070523/http://users.cvalley.net/canote/tornado.html |archive-date=February 6, 2007}}</ref> the year DC Comics absorbed All-American Publications.\n\nRon Goulart writes: \"Anticipating [[Wonder Woman]], that monumental creation of [[William Moulton Marston]], possibly even influencing it, Mayer chose a woman to be his costumed avenger, remaking the formidable Ma Hunkel into the even more formidable Red Tornado. Actually the people in the strip never knew the true sex of the Tornado. They only knew that this bulky figure in the red flannels, bedroom slippers, cape, and inverted stew pot could be counted on to tackle all sorts of criminals from the biggest to the smallest.\"<ref name=Goulart/>\n\nThe character reappeared in a three-page \"Scribbly\" story by Mayer in DC's ''Secret Origins'' #29 (Aug. 1986). She had a one-panel appearance in ''[[Animal Man]]'' \"Deus Ex Machine\", in a sort of limbo for characters who at the time weren't written into mainstream continuity.\n\nIn Alex Ross's classic 1996 graphic novel ''[[Kingdom Come (comics)|Kingdom Come]]'', set in an [[Elseworlds|alternative DC future]], the \"Original Red Tornado\" is identified as Ma Hunkel: she can just be seen at the top-left hand side of the Justice League line-up which includes [[Superman]] and [[Norman McCay]]. In issue 3, (page 135 of the collected edition), panel 1, she can be seen on a balcony looking down at Superman and McCay and wearing a far more sophisticated, armour-like costume.\n\nShe appeared briefly in 1998's ''DC Universe Holiday Bash II'' special, in the story \"I Left My Heart at the Justice Society Canteen\", and in ''All-Star Comics 80-Page Giant'' #1 (Sept. 1999), in a story, \"Way of the Amazon\", in which Ma Hunkel takes valorous center stage amid [[Liberty Belle (comics)|Liberty Belle]], [[Phantom Lady]] and [[Wonder Woman]]. She has continued to appear through the mid-2000s, mainly as a supporting character in ''[[Justice Society of America]]''.\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nIn the original comics in the 1940s, Ma Hunkel is a working mother whose costume consists of [[long underwear|longjohns]] and a [[cooking pot]] on her head. She adopts the identity of the Red Tornado to fight local criminals in her [[New York City]] neighborhood, inspired by her son's admiration for the superhero [[Alan Scott|Green Lantern]]. The character's popularity was such that she was given a cameo in the first adventure of the [[Justice Society of America]], visiting the JSA's headquarters but being forced by a humorous mishap, her pants splitting, to leave without having the chance to apply for membership. However, later Justice Society stories have declared Ma to be an honorary member of the team.\n\nMa was later joined by a pair of sidekicks known as the Cyclone Kids, consisting of her daughter Amelia \"Sisty\" Hunkel and neighbor Mortimer \"Dinky\" Jibbet (brother of boy cartoonist Scribbly, the star of the comic book feature in which the Red Tornado debuted).\n\nMa Hunkel returned in ''JSA'' #55 (February, 2004). This story reveals that Ma had been in the [[Witness Protection Program]] since 1950. Senior JSA members Green Lantern, [[Flash (Jay Garrick)|the Flash]], [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]], and [[Wildcat (DC Comics)|Wildcat]] find Ma to tell her that she can come out of hiding, as the last member of the gang against whom she testified in 1950 has died. Ma subsequently becomes caretaker of the JSA's [[Manhattan]] museum/headquarters. She does not, however, resume her crimefighting activities as the Red Tornado.\n\nHer daughter and (now) son-in-law, the former Cyclone Kids, briefly have their own costumed adventures, starting in the title ''[[Young Justice]]''. They band together with other Golden Age sidekicks out of concern for the safety of younger superheroes.<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Peter David|David, Peter]] |penciller=[[Todd Nauck|Nauck, Todd]] |inker=Stucker, Lary |letterer=[[Ken Lopez|Lopez, Ken]] |editor=[[Eddie Berganza|Berganza, Eddie]] |story=Aftermath |title=[[Young Justice]] |volume=1 |issue=16 |date=January 2000 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>\n\nMa's wind-controlling granddaughter, [[Maxine Hunkel]], joins the JSA in ''Justice Society of America'' Vol. 3 #1 (February, 2007). In ''Justice Society of America'' Vol. 3 #3 (March, 2007), Maxine adopts the alias \"[[Cyclone (DC Comics)|Cyclone]]\".\n\nMa's last name is frequently misspelled as \"Hunkle\".<ref>[http://www.wizkidsgames.com/heroclix/dc/figuregallery.asp?unitid=6521]{{dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref> Due to her bright red longjohns costume and roly-poly build, she is sometimes jokingly referred to as the Red Tomato.\n\nMa still has some fighting ability, using a mace and gas weaponry to help the younger JSA stun and delay members of the invading [[Injustice Society]]. She is taken hostage and frozen by the villain Icicle. She only suffered mild cold as the team's plans was not to kill or injure but steal from the JSA.<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Jen Van Meter|Van Meter, Jen]] |penciller=[[Pat Olliffe|Olliffe, Patrick]] |inker=Geraci, Drew |letterer=Fletcher, Jared K. |editor=Wacker, Stephen |story=Honor Among Thieves, Part 3 |title=JSA Classified |volume=1 |issue=7 |date=March 2006 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>\n\nMaxine was later responsible for the continuation of the Society as a viable team. When supernatural entities obliterated the brownstone, Jay Garrick believed this was a sign to end the team and move on. Maxine convinced him such an attitude was nonsensical and the Society was more than just a headquarters.<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Paul Levitz|Levitz, Paul]] |penciller=[[Jerry Ordway]], [[Luke Ross]] |inker=Dave Meikis, Jerry Ordway |letterer=Leigh, Rob |editor=Wacker, Stephen |story=Ghost in the Castle |title=JSA |volume=1 |issue=87 |date=September 2006 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>\n\n===The New 52===\nFollowing the [[Flashpoint (comics)|Flashpoint]] event, the [[DC Universe]] was [[reboot (fiction)|rebooted]] in 2011. Since then, a character resembling Ma Hunkel has appeared in the \"Channel 52\" back-up feature in a story set on the parallel world of [[Earth-Two|Earth-2]]. This character is younger and more svelte than the original version and appears to possess wind-based powers. It is unclear if this is a new version of Ma Hunkel.\n\n==Powers and abilities==\nIn her prime, Ma Hunkel was a surprisingly strong woman. Many who encountered her often believed that the Red Tornado was, in fact, a man, a notion that helped protect Ma's secret identity on more than one occasion. In the ensuing years, Ma Hunkel's strength level has diminished with age.\n\nMa Hunkel was also a great cook with an ability to feed a large group of people which included the Justice Society of America.\n\n==Other versions==\n\n===''Kingdom Come''===\nIn the ''[[Kingdom Come (comics)|Kingdom Come]]'' timeline, an older Ma Hunkel wielding a more sophisticated armor version of the Red Tornado costume joins the re-formed [[Justice League]] under [[Superman (Kingdom Come)|Superman]]<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Mark Waid|Waid, Mark]] |artist=[[Alex Ross|Ross, Alex]] |letterer=[[Todd Klein|Klein, Todd]] |editor=Kahan, Bob |story=Up in the Sky |title=[[Kingdom Come (comics)|Kingdom Come]] |volume=1 |issue=3 |date=July 1996 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>, and appears '''[[Maxine Hunkel]]'''. Maxine known as '''Red Tornado II''' or '''Cyclone''',  originally fought against [[Superman]]s [[Justice League]] after his return, before deciding to join it. She travels with the rest of the team to the Gulag to contain the prisoner revolt. [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Captain Marvel]] arrives and blasts the Gulag, freeing all the prisoners, who then attack the surrounding Justice League members.\n\n==In other media==\n\n===Television===\n* Ma Hunkel appeared in the ''[[Smallville]]'' two-hour [[Justice Society of America]] episode called \"[[Smallville: Absolute Justice]]\", portrayed by Deborah Cole. She gets arrested for supporting the JSA members.\n* Ma Hunkel is mentioned by [[Doctor Mid-Nite]] in the ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'' episode \"Crisis 22,300 Miles Above Earth!\"\n* Ma Hunkel's helmet appears in [[Rip Hunter]]'s office in ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]''.\n\n==Collected editions==\nThe Red Tornado is one of seven JSA-related heroes whose solo appearances are collected in an anthology entry in the [[DC Archive Editions]] series:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Material collected\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''JSA All-Stars Archives Vol. 1''' HC (2007)\n| valign=\"top\" | ''All-American Comics'' (1939 series) #20\u201324\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dcuguide.com/who.php?name=redtornado The Unofficial Red Tornado Biography]\n* [http://toonopedia.com/tornado1.htm Red Tornado (1940)] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6nNOVf01v?url=http://toonopedia.com/tornado1.htm Archived] from the original on January 9, 2017.\n{{Timeline\n|before= \u2190 The characters Batman and James Gordon were debuted by Bob Kane and Bill Finger. Other iconic debuts include the Batsuit and a version of the Batmobile. See [[Batman]], [[James Gordon (comics)]], [[Gotham City Police Department]], [[Batsuit]] and [[Batmobile]] for more info and the previous timeline. \n|title= [[Timeline of DC Comics]] ([[Timeline of DC Comics (1930s)|1930s]]) \n|years= April 1939\n|after = Wayne Manor was debuted by Bob Kane. See [[Wayne Manor]] for more info and next timeline. \u2192\n}}\n{{Justice Society of America}}\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n[[Category:All-American Publications characters]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1939]]\n[[Category:DC Comics female superheroes]]\n[[Category:Earth-Two]]\n[[Category:Golden Age superheroes]]\n[[Category:Parody superheroes]]\n[[Category:Fictional chefs]]\n", "text_old": ":''For information on the [[Silver Age of comic books|Silver Age]] Red Tornado, see [[Red Tornado]].''\n{{Infobox comics character <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image= Red Tornado Hunkel.jpg\n|caption=\"Ma\" Hunkel, the Golden Age Red Tornado.  Art by Sheldon Mayer.\n|character_name=Red Tornado\n|real_name=Abigail Mathilda \"Ma\" Hunkel\n|publisher=[[DC Comics]]\n|debut='''(As Ma Hunkel)''':<br> ''All-American Comics'' #3<br>(June 1939)<br>'''(As Red Tornado)''':<br> ''All-American Comics'' #20<br>(November 1940)\n|creators=[[Sheldon Mayer]]\n|alliances=[[Justice Society of America]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Great cook<br>Surprising physical strength       \n}}\n\nThe '''Red Tornado''' is a [[fictional character]], a [[superheroine]] in the [[DC Comics]] [[DC Universe|Universe]], debuting during the [[Golden Age of Comic Books]]. Created by [[Sheldon Mayer]], she [[first appeared]] in her civilian identity as '''Abigail Mathilda''' \"'''Ma'''\" '''Hunkel''' in [[All-American Publications]]' ''[[All-American Comics]]'' #3 (June 1939), and became the Red Tornado in ''All-American Comics'' #20 (Nov. 1940). As the Red Tornado, she was one of the first superhero [[parody|parodies]], as well as one of the first female superheroes (possibly the very first<ref>{{cite book |last=Coogan |first=Peter |date=2006 |title=Superhero: The Secret Origin of a Genre |url=https://books.google.com.au/books/about/Superhero.html?id=vnkrAQAAIAAJ |location=Austin, Texas |publisher=[[MonkeyBrain Books]] |page= |isbn=9781932265187 |author-link=Peter Coogan |access-date=July 4, 2007}}</ref>), and, when occasionally disguised as a man, comics' first cross-dressing heroine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ragnell.blogspot.com/2006/05/mama-thon-red-tornado.html |title=Mama-Thon -- The Red Tornado |author=Ragnell |date=May 11, 2006 |website=Written World |publisher= |access-date=December 1, 2006 |quote=}}</ref> ([[Madame Fatal]], earlier that year, was the first cross-dressing hero.)\n\n==Publication history==\nInitially as simply Ma Hunkel, the Golden Age Red Tornado originated in Sheldon Mayer's semi-autobiographical humor feature ''[[Scribbly the Boy Cartoonist]]'' in ''All-American Comics''.<ref name=Toonopedia>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |title=Scribbly the Boy Cartoonist |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/scribbly.htm |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nWith the skyrocketing popularity of the ''[[Superman]]'' comic in 1938, comic book publishers began featuring their own superhero characters. ''All-American Comics'' responded in 1939 with [[Gary Concord, the Ultra-Man]], and followed in 1940 with [[Green Lantern]] and [[the Atom]]. The superhero trend was so powerful that in the ''Scribbly'' story in issue #20 (Nov 1940), Ma Hunkel became a superhero herself.<ref>{{cite book |last=Coogan |first=Peter |date=2006 |title=Superhero: The Secret Origin of a Genre |pages=26-27 |location=Austin, Texas |publisher=[[MonkeyBrain Books]] |page= |isbn=9781932265187 |author-link=Peter Coogan}}</ref> In the story, Scribbly's little brother and Ma Hunkel's daughter Sisty are kidnapped, and the police are unable to locate them. Scribbly tells Ma about the Green Lantern, and she's inspired to don a costume and fight crime, calling herself the Red Tornado. By issue #23, the Red Tornado was sharing billing with Scribbly, and in #24, Ma's two kids joined the fight against crime, calling themselves \"the Cyclone Twins\".<ref name=\"Goulart\">{{cite book |last1=Goulart |first1=Ron |title=The Encyclopedia of American Comics: From 1897 to the Present |date=1990 |publisher=Facts on File |isbn=0-8160-1852-9 |pages=322-323}}</ref> The series continued for three more years as \"Scribbly & the Red Tornado\".<ref name=Toonopedia/>\n\nThe feature ran through ''All-American Comics'' #59, in 1944,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://users.cvalley.net/canote/tornado.html |title=Justice Society Profile: Red Tornado |last=Canote |first=Terry |date= |website=Terry Canote's Homepage |publisher= |access-date=December 1, 2006 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206070523/http://users.cvalley.net/canote/tornado.html |archive-date=February 6, 2007}}</ref> the year DC Comics absorbed All-American Publications.\n\nRon Goulart writes: \"Anticipating [[Wonder Woman]], that monumental creation of [[William Moulton Marston]], possibly even influencing it, Mayer chose a woman to be his costumed avenger, remaking the formidable Ma Hunkel into the even more formidable Red Tornado. Actually the people in the strip never knew the true sex of the Tornado. They only knew that this bulky figure in the red flannels, bedroom slippers, cape, and inverted stew pot could be counted on to tackle all sorts of criminals from the biggest to the smallest.\"<ref name=Goulart/>\n\nThe character reappeared in a three-page \"Scribbly\" story by Mayer in DC's ''Secret Origins'' #29 (Aug. 1986). She had a one-panel appearance in ''[[Animal Man]]'' \"Deus Ex Machine\", in a sort of limbo for characters who at the time weren't written into mainstream continuity.\n\nIn Alex Ross's classic 1996 graphic novel ''[[Kingdom Come (comics)|Kingdom Come]]'', set in an [[Elseworlds|alternative DC future]], the \"Original Red Tornado\" is identified as Ma Hunkel: she can just be seen at the top-left hand side of the Justice League line-up which includes [[Superman]] and [[Norman McCay]]. In issue 3, (page 135 of the collected edition), panel 1, she can be seen on a balcony looking down at Superman and McCay and wearing a far more sophisticated, armour-like costume.\n\nShe appeared briefly in 1998's ''DC Universe Holiday Bash II'' special, in the story \"I Left My Heart at the Justice Society Canteen\", and in ''All-Star Comics 80-Page Giant'' #1 (Sept. 1999), in a story, \"Way of the Amazon\", in which Ma Hunkel takes valorous center stage amid [[Liberty Belle (comics)|Liberty Belle]], [[Phantom Lady]] and [[Wonder Woman]]. She has continued to appear through the mid-2000s, mainly as a supporting character in ''[[Justice Society of America]]''.\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nIn the original comics in the 1940s, Ma Hunkel is a working mother whose costume consists of [[long underwear|longjohns]] and a [[cooking pot]] on her head. She adopts the identity of the Red Tornado to fight local criminals in her [[New York City]] neighborhood, inspired by her son's admiration for the superhero [[Alan Scott|Green Lantern]]. The character's popularity was such that she was given a cameo in the first adventure of the [[Justice Society of America]], visiting the JSA's headquarters but being forced by a humorous mishap, her pants splitting, to leave without having the chance to apply for membership. However, later Justice Society stories have declared Ma to be an honorary member of the team.\n\nMa was later joined by a pair of sidekicks known as the Cyclone Kids, consisting of her daughter Amelia \"Sisty\" Hunkel and neighbor Mortimer \"Dinky\" Jibbet (brother of boy cartoonist Scribbly, the star of the comic book feature in which the Red Tornado debuted).\n\nMa Hunkel returned in ''JSA'' #55 (February, 2004). This story reveals that Ma had been in the [[Witness Protection Program]] since 1950. Senior JSA members Green Lantern, [[Flash (Jay Garrick)|the Flash]], [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]], and [[Wildcat (comics)|Wildcat]] find Ma to tell her that she can come out of hiding, as the last member of the gang against whom she testified in 1950 has died. Ma subsequently becomes caretaker of the JSA's [[Manhattan]] museum/headquarters. She does not, however, resume her crimefighting activities as the Red Tornado.\n\nHer daughter and (now) son-in-law, the former Cyclone Kids, briefly have their own costumed adventures, starting in the title ''[[Young Justice]]''. They band together with other Golden Age sidekicks out of concern for the safety of younger superheroes.<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Peter David|David, Peter]] |penciller=[[Todd Nauck|Nauck, Todd]] |inker=Stucker, Lary |letterer=[[Ken Lopez|Lopez, Ken]] |editor=[[Eddie Berganza|Berganza, Eddie]] |story=Aftermath |title=[[Young Justice]] |volume=1 |issue=16 |date=January 2000 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>\n\nMa's wind-controlling granddaughter, [[Maxine Hunkel]], joins the JSA in ''Justice Society of America'' Vol. 3 #1 (February, 2007). In ''Justice Society of America'' Vol. 3 #3 (March, 2007), Maxine adopts the alias \"[[Cyclone (DC Comics)|Cyclone]]\".\n\nMa's last name is frequently misspelled as \"Hunkle\".<ref>[http://www.wizkidsgames.com/heroclix/dc/figuregallery.asp?unitid=6521]{{dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref> Due to her bright red longjohns costume and roly-poly build, she is sometimes jokingly referred to as the Red Tomato.\n\nMa still has some fighting ability, using a mace and gas weaponry to help the younger JSA stun and delay members of the invading [[Injustice Society]]. She is taken hostage and frozen by the villain Icicle. She only suffered mild cold as the team's plans was not to kill or injure but steal from the JSA.<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Jen Van Meter|Van Meter, Jen]] |penciller=[[Pat Olliffe|Olliffe, Patrick]] |inker=Geraci, Drew |letterer=Fletcher, Jared K. |editor=Wacker, Stephen |story=Honor Among Thieves, Part 3 |title=JSA Classified |volume=1 |issue=7 |date=March 2006 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>\n\nMaxine was later responsible for the continuation of the Society as a viable team. When supernatural entities obliterated the brownstone, Jay Garrick believed this was a sign to end the team and move on. Maxine convinced him such an attitude was nonsensical and the Society was more than just a headquarters.<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Paul Levitz|Levitz, Paul]] |penciller=[[Jerry Ordway]], [[Luke Ross]] |inker=Dave Meikis, Jerry Ordway |letterer=Leigh, Rob |editor=Wacker, Stephen |story=Ghost in the Castle |title=JSA |volume=1 |issue=87 |date=September 2006 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>\n\n===The New 52===\nFollowing the [[Flashpoint (comics)|Flashpoint]] event, the [[DC Universe]] was [[reboot (fiction)|rebooted]] in 2011. Since then, a character resembling Ma Hunkel has appeared in the \"Channel 52\" back-up feature in a story set on the parallel world of [[Earth-Two|Earth-2]]. This character is younger and more svelte than the original version and appears to possess wind-based powers. It is unclear if this is a new version of Ma Hunkel.\n\n==Powers and abilities==\nIn her prime, Ma Hunkel was a surprisingly strong woman. Many who encountered her often believed that the Red Tornado was, in fact, a man, a notion that helped protect Ma's secret identity on more than one occasion. In the ensuing years, Ma Hunkel's strength level has diminished with age.\n\nMa Hunkel was also a great cook with an ability to feed a large group of people which included the Justice Society of America.\n\n==Other versions==\n\n===''Kingdom Come''===\nIn the ''[[Kingdom Come (comics)|Kingdom Come]]'' timeline, an older Ma Hunkel wielding a more sophisticated armor version of the Red Tornado costume joins the re-formed [[Justice League]] under [[Superman (Kingdom Come)|Superman]]<ref>{{Cite comic |writer=[[Mark Waid|Waid, Mark]] |artist=[[Alex Ross|Ross, Alex]] |letterer=[[Todd Klein|Klein, Todd]] |editor=Kahan, Bob |story=Up in the Sky |title=[[Kingdom Come (comics)|Kingdom Come]] |volume=1 |issue=3 |date=July 1996 |publisher=[[DC Comics]] |location=New York, NY |page=}}</ref>, and appears '''[[Maxine Hunkel]]'''. Maxine known as '''Red Tornado II''' or '''Cyclone''',  originally fought against [[Superman]]s [[Justice League]] after his return, before deciding to join it. She travels with the rest of the team to the Gulag to contain the prisoner revolt. [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Captain Marvel]] arrives and blasts the Gulag, freeing all the prisoners, who then attack the surrounding Justice League members.\n\n==In other media==\n\n===Television===\n* Ma Hunkel appeared in the ''[[Smallville]]'' two-hour [[Justice Society of America]] episode called \"[[Smallville: Absolute Justice]]\", portrayed by Deborah Cole. She gets arrested for supporting the JSA members.\n* Ma Hunkel is mentioned by [[Doctor Mid-Nite]] in the ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'' episode \"Crisis 22,300 Miles Above Earth!\"\n* Ma Hunkel's helmet appears in [[Rip Hunter]]'s office in ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]''.\n\n==Collected editions==\nThe Red Tornado is one of seven JSA-related heroes whose solo appearances are collected in an anthology entry in the [[DC Archive Editions]] series:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Material collected\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''JSA All-Stars Archives Vol. 1''' HC (2007)\n| valign=\"top\" | ''All-American Comics'' (1939 series) #20\u201324\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dcuguide.com/who.php?name=redtornado The Unofficial Red Tornado Biography]\n* [http://toonopedia.com/tornado1.htm Red Tornado (1940)] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6nNOVf01v?url=http://toonopedia.com/tornado1.htm Archived] from the original on January 9, 2017.\n{{Timeline\n|before= \u2190 The characters Batman and James Gordon were debuted by Bob Kane and Bill Finger. Other iconic debuts include the Batsuit and a version of the Batmobile. See [[Batman]], [[James Gordon (comics)]], [[Gotham City Police Department]], [[Batsuit]] and [[Batmobile]] for more info and the previous timeline. \n|title= [[Timeline of DC Comics]] ([[Timeline of DC Comics (1930s)|1930s]]) \n|years= April 1939\n|after = Wayne Manor was debuted by Bob Kane. See [[Wayne Manor]] for more info and next timeline. \u2192\n}}\n{{Justice Society of America}}\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n[[Category:All-American Publications characters]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1939]]\n[[Category:DC Comics female superheroes]]\n[[Category:Earth-Two]]\n[[Category:Golden Age superheroes]]\n[[Category:Parody superheroes]]\n[[Category:Fictional chefs]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toWildcat (disambiguation)(link changed toWildcat (DC Comics)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Tornado_(Ma_Hunkel)"}
{"title_page": "Secret Origins", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title               = Secret Origins\n|image               = Secret Origins TPB.jpg\n|caption             = [[Brian Bolland]]'s cover to the 1989 ''Secret Origins'' collection\n|schedule            = Monthly\n|limited             =\n|ongoing             = y\n|1shot               =\n|Superhero           = y\n|publisher           = [[DC Comics]]\n|date                = '''One-shot:'''<br>Summer 1961<br>'''Vol. 1'''<br>February\u2013March 1973; October\u2013November 1974<br>'''Vol. 2''':<br>April 1986 \u2013 August 1990<br>'''Vol. 3''':<br>June 2014 \u2013 May 2015\n|issues              = '''One-shot:''' 1<br>'''Vol. 1''': 7<br>'''Vol. 2''': 50, plus 3 ''Annual''s and 1 ''Special''<br>'''Vol. 3''': 11  \n|main_char_team      =\n|writers             =\n|artists             =\n|pencillers          =\n|inkers              =\n|letterers           =\n|colorists           =\n|editors             = [[Roy Thomas]]<br>[[Mark Waid]]\n|creative_team_month =\n|creative_team_year  =\n|creators            =\n|TPB                 = Secret Origins\n|ISBN                = 0-930289-50-1\n|TPB#                =\n|ISBN#               =\n|subcat              = DC Comics\n|altcat              =\n|sort                = Secret Origins\n|addpubcat#          =\n|nonUS               =\n}}\n'''''Secret Origins''''' is the title of several [[comic book]] series published by [[DC Comics]] which featured the [[Origin story|origin stories]] of the publisher's various characters.\n\n==Publication history==\n''Secret Origins'' was first published as a [[One-shot (comics)|one-shot]] in 1961 and contained only reprinted material.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=1471|title= ''Secret Origins'' one-shot}}</ref> The title became an ongoing reprint series in February&ndash;March 1973 which ran for seven issues and ended in October\u2013November 1974.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=2104|title= ''Secret Origins''}}</ref> The title was used on various compilations of origin stories, including ''[[Limited Collectors' Edition]]'' #C-39: ''Secret Origins Super-Villains'' (October\u2013November 1975)<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 68954|title= ''Limited Collectors' Edition'' #C-39}}</ref> and #C-45: ''More Secret Origins Super-Villains'' (June\u2013July 1976)<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 68959|title= ''Limited Collectors' Edition'' #C-45}}</ref> as well as ''[[DC Special Series]]'' #10 (1978)<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 31908|title= ''DC Special Series'' #10}}</ref> and #19 (Fall 1979).<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 33806|title= ''DC Special Series'' #19}}</ref> Its most well-known incarnation was a 50-issue series that ran from April 1986 to August 1990,<ref>{{gcdb series|id=3166|title= ''Secret Origins'' vol. 2}}</ref> plus three ''Annual''s<ref>{{gcdb series|id=3377|title= ''Secret Origins Annual''}}</ref> and one ''Special''.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=3819|title= ''Secret Origins Special''}}</ref> Typically, an issue would clarify the [[Crisis on Infinite Earths|Post-''Crisis'']] origins of a number of characters,<ref>{{cite book|last=Manning|first= Matthew K.|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1980s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year= 2010|location= London, United Kingdom|isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9|page= 218|quote = The heroes of the DC Universe got a little more exposed thanks to the new ongoing effort ''Secret Origins'', a title offering new interpretations to the backgrounds of some of comics' biggest icons.}}</ref> usually two as most of the issues were double-sized, i.e. 48 pages. [[Roy Thomas]] was the initial writer/editorial consultant on the series; later issues were overseen by [[Mark Waid]]. Two more specials followed in 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=5994|title= ''Secret Origins 80-Page Giant''}} and {{gcdb series|id=10200|title= ''Secret Origins of Super-Villains 80-Page Giant''}}</ref> In 2004, it returned to the all-reprint format with a ''Weird Secret Origins'' special featuring [[Doctor Fate]], the [[Spectre (DC Comics character)|Spectre]], [[Animal Man]], the [[Enchantress (DC Comics)|Enchantress]], [[Metamorpho]], [[Congorilla]], [[El Diablo (comics)|El Diablo]], and the [[Bizarro World]].\n\nA new monthly incarnation focusing on characters in ''[[The New 52]]'', launched in April 2014 with a June 2014 [[cover date]]. The first issue featured the origins of [[Superman]], [[Supergirl]] and the [[Dick Grayson]] version of [[Robin (character)|Robin]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=50240|title= Exclusive: DC's ''Secret Origins'' & Tomasi's ''Batman Vs. Bane'' To Debut in April|first= Steve|last= Sunu|date= January 13, 2014|website= [[Comic Book Resources]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140712085611/http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=50240|archivedate= July 12, 2014|url-status= live}} Archive requires scrolldown</ref> This series was cancelled as of issue #11 (May 2015)<ref>{{gcdb series|id= 80309|title= ''Secret Origins'' vol. 3}}</ref> on sale in March 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-12/16/dc-cancellations|title= DC Comics cancels half its line from March 2015|first= Matt|last= Kamen|date= December 16, 2014|magazine= [[Wired UK]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150908083204/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-12/16/dc-cancellations|archivedate= September 8, 2015|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Characters featured in the 1986\u20131990 series==\n* '''#1''' (April 1986): The [[Golden Age of Comics|Golden Age]] [[Superman (Earth-Two)|Superman]]; this was intended as a tribute to the original version of the character, as the latter-day version of Superman was being concurrently introduced by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] in the ''[[The Man of Steel (comic book)|Man Of Steel]]'' miniseries; art by Golden Age Superman artist [[Wayne Boring]] and [[Jerry Ordway]].\n* '''#2''' (May 1986): The [[Blue Beetle]], both the Dan Garrett and Ted Kord versions; art by [[Gil Kane]].\n* '''#3''' (June 1986): [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Captain Marvel]] credited by the ''Shazam!'' title; a retelling of the story from ''WHIZ Comics'' #2, albeit updated to modern day.  Much of this was changed in the ''[[Legends (comics)|Legends]]'' crossover, Thomas himself would [[Retroactive continuity|retcon]] this some months later in ''[[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)#Captain Marvel in the late 1980s|SHAZAM! The New Beginning]]'', and all of which was changed again by Jerry Ordway in his [[graphic novel]] ''[[The Power of Shazam!]]''.\n* '''#4''' (July 1986): [[Firestorm (comics)|Firestorm]] (Ronnie Raymond).\n* '''#5''' (August 1986): the original [[Crimson Avenger (Lee Travis)|Crimson Avenger]]; art by [[Gene Colan]].\n* '''#6''' (September 1986): [[Halo (comics)|Halo]] of the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]]; the Golden Age [[Batman (Earth-Two)|Batman]]. This was the first double-sized issue.\n* '''#7''' (October 1986): [[Guy Gardner (comics)|Guy Gardner]]; the Golden Age [[Sandman (Wesley Dodds)|Sandman]]\n* '''#8''' (November 1986): [[Shadow Lass]]; [[Doll Man]].\n* '''#9''' (December 1986): The original [[Star-Spangled Kid]] (Skyman) and [[Stripesy]]; the Golden Age [[Flash (Jay Garrick)|Flash]].\n* '''#10''' (January 1987): The [[Phantom Stranger]]. This was a ''[[Legends (comics)|Legends]]'' tie-in that related four possible origins for the character; one by Mike Barr and [[Jim Aparo]] was a variation on the [[Wandering Jew]] myth, while another by [[Alan Moore]] and [[Joe Orlando]] postulated that the Stranger was a fallen angel.\n* '''#11''' (February 1987): the Golden Age [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]]; [[Power Girl]]. Both stories presented have since been retconned, with Power Girl's backstory having been redefined by [[Geoff Johns]] in the pages of ''JSA Classified'', which served as part of the buildup to ''[[Infinite Crisis]]''.\n* '''#12''' (March 1987): The [[Challengers of the Unknown]]; [[Fury (DC Comics)|Fury]].\n* '''#13''' (April 1987): [[Dick Grayson|Nightwing]] (art by [[Erik Larsen]]); [[Johnny Thunder#Original version|Johnny Thunder and his Thunderbolt]]; the Whip.\n* '''#14''' (May 1987): [[Suicide Squad]]. Another ''Legends'' tie-in, it served as a prequel to the later series and was written by that series' writer, [[John Ostrander]].\n* '''#15''' (June 1987): The [[Spectre (DC Comics character)|Spectre]]; [[Deadman (DC Comics)|Deadman]].\n* '''#16''' (July 1987): [[Hourman]]; the [[Warlord (DC Comics)|Warlord]]; [['Mazing Man]].\n* '''#17''' (August 1987): [[Adam Strange]]; [[Doctor Occult]].\n* '''#18''' (September 1987): The Golden Age Green Lantern ([[Alan Scott]]); the [[Creeper (comics)|Creeper]].\n* '''#19''' (October 1987): [[Uncle Sam (comics)|Uncle Sam]]; the [[Guardian (DC Comics)|Guardian]].\n* '''#20''' (November 1987): [[Barbara Gordon|Batgirl]]; [[Doctor Mid-Nite]].\n* '''#21''' (December 1987): [[Jonah Hex]]; the [[Black Condor]].\n* '''#22''' (January 1988): the [[Manhunters (DC Comics)|Manhunters]]. This was a tie-in with ''[[Millennium (comics)|Millennium]]'' as was the subsequent issue, and aligned the various histories of the characters with the [[Manhunter (comics)|Manhunter]] name together.\n* '''#23''' (February 1988): the [[Guardians of the Universe]] written by [[Todd Klein]]; the [[Floronic Man]] written by [[Rick Veitch]].\n* '''#24''' (March 1988): [[Doctor Fate]]; [[Blue Devil (DC Comics)|Blue Devil]]. Mark Waid became editor beginning with this issue.\n* '''#25''' (April 1988): The [[Legion of Super-Heroes]] (now apocryphal); the Golden Age [[Atom (Al Pratt)|Atom]].\n* '''#26''' (May 1988): [[Black Lightning]]; [[Miss America (DC Comics)|Miss America]].\n* '''#27''' (June 1988): [[Zatanna]], her father [[Zatara]], and [[Doctor Mist]].\n* '''#28''' (July 1988): [[Midnight (comics)|Midnight]] art by Gil Kane; [[Nightshade (DC Comics)|Nightshade]] art by [[Rob Liefeld]].  Nightshade's origin doubled as an introduction/backdrop to a three-issue ''Suicide Squad'' story arc where she returned to her place of origin to save her brother.\n* '''#29''' (August 1988): The [[Atom (Ray Palmer)|Atom]]; the [[Red Tornado (Golden Age)|Red Tornado]] (Ma Hunkel; this was [[Sheldon Mayer]]'s last comic book story); [[Tex Thompson|Mr. America]] (a.k.a. the Americommando).\n* '''#30''' (September 1988): [[Plastic Man]]; the [[Elongated Man]].\n* '''#31''' (October 1988): The [[Justice Society of America]]. A full-length story, and Roy Thomas' last contribution to the series, excluding the Grim Ghost story in #42.\n* '''#32''' (November 1988): The [[Justice League|Justice League of America]]. In a full-length story by [[Keith Giffen]] and [[Peter David]], the Justice League is formed by [[Green Lantern]] ([[Hal Jordan]]), the [[Flash (Barry Allen)]], [[Aquaman]], the Martian Manhunter and the Black Canary. Superman and Batman were not founding members, and [[Wonder Woman]]'s revised continuity precluded her from the same. The events depicted were later expanded upon in ''JLA: Year One'' and ''JLA: Incarnations''.\n* '''#33''' (December 1988): [[Fire (DC Comics)|Fire]], [[Ice (comics)|Ice]] and [[Mister Miracle]]. This and the subsequent two issues dealt with the members of Justice League International.\n* '''#34''' (Winter 1988): [[Captain Atom]], [[G'nort]] and [[Rocket Red]].\n* '''#35''' (Holiday 1988): [[Booster Gold]], [[Maxwell Lord]], and the [[Martian Manhunter]] rendered apocryphal by events and revelations in J'onn J'onnz' later solo series.\n* '''#36''' (January 1989): Green Lantern ([[Hal Jordan]]) story by [[Christopher Priest (comics)|Jim Owsley]]; [[Poison Ivy (character)|Poison Ivy]] story by [[Neil Gaiman]].\n* '''#37''' (February 1989): The [[Legion of Substitute Heroes]]; the original [[Doctor Light (Arthur Light)|Doctor Light]].\n* '''#38''' (March 1989): The [[Green Arrow]] and [[Roy Harper (comics)|Speedy]].\n* '''#39''' (April 1989): [[Animal Man]] story by [[Grant Morrison]]; the [[Man-Bat]].\n* '''#40''' (May 1989): The [[Gorillas in comics|all-gorilla]] issue, spotlighting [[Congorilla]], [[Detective Chimp]], and [[Gorilla Grodd]].\n* '''#41''' (June 1989): The [[Rogues (comics)|Flash's Rogues Gallery]] - the [[Weather Wizard]], [[Heat Wave (comics)|Heat Wave]], the [[Trickster (comics)|Trickster]], the [[Pied Piper (comics)|Pied Piper]], [[Captain Boomerang]], and [[Captain Cold]].\n* '''#42''' (July 1989): [[Phantom Girl]]; the [[Gay Ghost]]/Grim Ghost.\n* '''#43''' (August 1989): The original [[Hawk and Dove]]; [[Cave Carson]]; [[Chris KL-99]].\n* '''#44''' (September 1989): [[Clayface]] I, II, III and IV. This issue gave background information for a story arc that appeared in ''[[Detective Comics]]'' #604-607 entitled ''The Mud Pack''.\n* '''#45''' (October 1989): [[Blackhawk (DC Comics)|Blackhawk]]; [[El Diablo (comics)|El Diablo]].\n* '''#46''' (December 1989): The headquarters of the Silver Age Justice League of America (story by Grant Morrison), the New Titans' [[Titans Tower]], and the 'rocketship clubhouse' of the Legion of Super Heroes. Arm Fall Off Boy makes his first appearance.\n* '''#47''' (February 1990): Deceased Legionnaires [[Ferro Lad]], [[Karate Kid (comics)|Karate Kid]] and [[Chemical King]].\n* '''#48''' (April 1990): [[Ambush Bug]], [[Stanley and His Monster]], [[Rex the Wonder Dog]], and the [[Trigger Twins]].\n* '''#49''' (June 1990): [[Bouncing Boy]], the [[Newsboy Legion]], and the [[Silent Knight]].\n* '''#50''' (August 1990): a 96-page last issue. This consisted of a [[prose]] retelling of [[Robin (character)|Dick Grayson]]'s first encounter with Batman by [[Dennis O'Neil]] and [[George P\u00e9rez]]; the first meeting of the Golden and Silver Age [[Flash (comics)|Flash]]es story by Grant Morrison; how [[Johnny Thunder#Western version|Johnny Thunder (the western hero)]] came to be; the definitive history of the [[Black Canary]]; and the stories behind the [[Dolphin (comics)|Dolphin]] and the [[Space Museum (comics)|Space Museum]].\n\n===''Annual''s and ''Special''s===\n* '''''Annual'' #1''' (1987): the [[Doom Patrol]] art by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]]; [[Captain Comet]].\n* '''''Annual'' #2''' (1988): The second and third Flashes ([[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen]] and [[Wally West]]).\n* '''''Annual'' #3''' (1989): the [[Teen Titans]]. This was an anniversary tribute with contributions from [[George P\u00e9rez]], [[Tom Grummett]], [[Irv Novick]], [[Dave Cockrum]], [[Kevin Maguire (artist)|Kevin Maguire]] and [[Colleen Doran]]. It also included five pages of ''[[Who's Who in the DC Universe|Who's Who]]'' entries on [[Bette Kane|Flamebird]], the [[Golden Eagle (comics)|Golden Eagle]], the [[Bumblebee (comics)|Bumblebee]], the [[Mal Duncan|Herald]], the Antithesis and the [[Mister Twister (comics)|Gargoyle]].\n* '''''Special'' #1''' (1989): the [[Penguin (character)|Penguin]] by [[Alan Grant (writer)|Alan Grant]] and [[Sam Kieth]], the [[Riddler]] by Neil Gaiman, [[Matt Wagner]] and [[Bernie Mireault]], and [[Two-Face]] by [[Mark Verheiden]] and [[Pat Broderick]].\n\nAdditionally, there was a belated ''Secret Origins 80-Page Giant'' issued in 1998 ({{ISBN|1-56389-440-8}}), that focused on the members of [[Young Justice]].\n\n==Collected edition==\nSome issues of the second series were collected in a [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]] along with other material and some original work in 1989 called ''Secret Origins'', but the official title, as stated in the book's [[Indicia (publishing)|indicia]], is given as ''Secret Origins of The World's Greatest Super-Heroes'' ({{ISBN|0930289501}}). The focus was on DC's major characters: origin of the Justice League of America (from #32), the Flash (Barry Allen, from ''Secret Origins Annual'' #2); Green Lantern (Hal Jordan, from #36); J'onn J'onnz, the Martian Manhunter (from #35); and Superman (from ''The Man of Steel'' #6). There was also an all-new retelling of Batman's origins, ''[[The Man Who Falls|Batman: The Man Who Falls]]'', by Dennis O'Neil and [[Dick Giordano]]; this story later served as a cited inspiration for the [[2005 in film|2005 film]] ''[[Batman Begins]]''.<ref name=\"genesis\">{{cite video | people=[[Dan DiDio|DiDio, Dan]] (Vice President of DC Comics), [[David S. Goyer|Goyer, David S.]] (Co-writer), [[Paul Levitz|Levitz, Paul]] (President - [[DC Comics]]), [[Christopher Nolan|Nolan, Christopher]] (Director), Schreck, Bob (Batman Editor - DC Comics)|date=2006|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0485650/|title=Genesis of the Bat | medium=DVD featurette}}</ref>\n\n==Characters featured in the 2014\u201315 series==\n \n* '''#1''' (June 2014): [[Superman]], [[Robin (character)|Robin]] ([[Dick Grayson]]), [[Supergirl]]\n* '''#2''' (July 2014): [[Batman]], [[Aquaman]], [[Starfire (Koriand'r)|Starfire]]\n* '''#3''' (August 2014): [[Green Lantern]] ([[Hal Jordan]]), [[Batwoman|Batwoman (Kate Kane)]], [[Red Robin (comics)|Red Robin]] ([[Tim Drake]])\n* '''#4''' (September 2014): [[Harley Quinn]], the [[Green Arrow]], [[Damian Wayne]]\n* '''#5''' (October 2014): [[Cyborg (comics)|Cyborg]], the [[Red Hood]] ([[Jason Todd]]), [[Mera (comics)|Mera]]\n* '''#6''' (December 2014): [[Wonder Woman]], [[Deadman (DC Comics)|Deadman]], [[Sinestro]]\n* '''#7''' (January 2015): The [[Flash (comics)|Flash]], the [[Huntress (comics)|Huntress]], [[Superboy]]\n* '''#8''' (February 2015): [[Dick Grayson|Grayson]], [[Animal Man]], [[Katana (comics)|Katana]]\n* '''#9''' (March 2015): The [[Swamp Thing]], [[Power Girl]], [[Green Lantern]] ([[John Stewart (comics)|John Stewart]])\n* '''#10''' (April 2015): [[Batgirl]], [[Firestorm (comics)|Firestorm]], [[Poison Ivy (character)|Poison Ivy]]\n* '''#11''' (May 2015): The [[Black Canary]], [[Guy Gardner (comics)|Green Lantern (Guy Gardner)]], [[John Constantine]]\n\n===Collected editions 2014\u201315 series===\n* ''Secret Origins Volume 1'' - collects ''Secret Origins'' (vol. 3) #1-4 (Feb. 2015)\n* ''Secret Origins Volume 2'' - collects ''Secret Origins'' (vol. 3) #5-11 (Aug. 2015)\n\n==''Secret Origins of Super-Heroes''==\nDuring ''[[52 (comics)|52]]'', Weeks 12 through 51 featured two-page origins of various superheroes, written by [[Mark Waid]]. The origins featured were:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*Week 12: [[Wonder Woman]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= [[Mark Waid|Waid, Mark]]|penciller= [[Adam Hughes|Hughes, Adam]]|inker= Hughes, Adam|story= The Origin of Wonder Woman|title= [[52 (comics)|52]]|issue= #12|date= September 2006 [July 26, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 13: The [[Elongated Man]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Kevin Nowlan|Nowlan, Kevin]]|inker= Nowlan, Kevin|story= The Origin of Elongated Man|title= 52|issue= #13|date= October 2006 [August 2, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 14: [[Metamorpho]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Eric Powell (comics)|Powell, Eric]]|inker= Powell, Eric|story= The Origin of Metamorpho, the Element Man|title= 52|issue= #14|date= October 2006 [August 9, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 15: [[John Henry Irons|Steel]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Jon Bogdanove|Bogdanove, Jon]]|inker= Bogdanove, Jon|story= The Origin of Steel|title= 52|issue= #15|date= October 2006 [August 16, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 16: [[Black Adam]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[J. G. Jones|Jones, J. G.]]|inker= Jones, J. G.|story= The Origin of Black Adam|title= 52|issue= #16|date= October 2006 [August 23, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 17: [[Lobo (DC Comics)|Lobo]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Keith Giffen|Giffen, Keith]]|inker= Jadson, Jack|story= The Origin of Lobo|title= 52|issue= #17|date= October 2006 [August 30, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 18: The [[Question (comics)|Question]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Joe Bennett (artist)|Bennett, Joe]]|inker= Bennett, Joe|story= The Origin of the Question|title= 52|issue= #18|date= November 2006 [September 6, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 19: [[Animal Man]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Brian Bolland|Bolland, Brian]]|inker= Mardon, Mark|story= The Origin of Animal Man|title= 52|issue= #19|date= November 2006 [September 13, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 20: [[Adam Strange]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= Nowlan, Kevin|inker= Nowlan, Kevin|story= The Origin of Adam Strange|title= 52|issue= #20|date= November 2006 [September 20, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 22: [[Hal Jordan|Green Lantern]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Ivan Reis|Reis, Ivan]]|inker= Albert, Oclair|story= The Origin of Green Lantern|title= 52|issue= #22|date= December 2006 [October 4, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 23: [[Wildcat (DC Comics)|Wildcat]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Jerry Ordway|Ordway, Jerry]]|inker= Ordway, Jerry|story= The Origin of Wildcat|title= 52|issue= #23|date= December 2006 [October 11, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 24: [[Booster Gold]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Dan Jurgens|Jurgens, Dan]]|inker= [[Andy Lanning|Lanning, Andy]]|story= The Origin of Booster Gold|title= 52|issue= #24|date= December 2006 [October 18, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 25: [[Dick Grayson|Nightwing]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[George P\u00e9rez|P\u00e9rez, George]]|inker= P\u00e9rez, George|story= The Origin of Nightwing|title= 52|issue= #25|date= December 2006 [October 25, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 26: [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]] and [[Hawkgirl]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= Bennett, Joe|inker= Jose, Ruy|story= The Origin of Hawkman and Hawkgirl|title= 52|issue= #26|date= January 2007 [November 1, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 27: The [[Black Canary]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Howard Chaykin|Chaykin, Howard]]|inker= Chaykin, Howard|story= The Origin of Black Canary|title= 52|issue= #27|date= January 2007 [November 8, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 28: The [[Catman (comics)|Catman]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Dale Eaglesham|Eaglesham, Dale]]|inker= [[Art Thibert|Thibert, Art]]|story= The Origin of Catman|title= 52|issue= #28|date= January 2007 [November 15, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 30: The [[Metal Men]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Duncan Rouleau|Rouleau, Duncan]]|inker= Rouleau, Duncan|story= The Origin of the Metal Men|title= 52|issue= #30|date= January 2007 [November 29, 2006]}}</ref>\n{{col-2}} \n*Week 31: [[Robin (Tim Drake)|Robin]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Freddie Williams II|Williams II, Freddie]]|inker= Williams II, Freddie|story= The Origin of Robin|title= 52|issue= #31|date= February 2007 [December 6, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 32: The [[Blue Beetle (Jaime Reyes)|Blue Beetle]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Cully Hamner|Hamner, Cully]]|inker= Hamner, Cully|story= The Origin of Blue Beetle|title= 52|issue= #32|date= February 2007 [December 13, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 33: The [[Martian Manhunter]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Tom Mandrake|Mandrake, Tom]]|inker= Mandrake, Tom|story= The Origin of Martian Manunter|title= 52|issue= #33|date= February 2007 [December 20, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 34: [[Zatanna]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= Bolland, Brian|inker= Bolland, Brian|story= The Origin of Zatanna|title= 52|issue= #34|date= February 2007 [December 27, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 36: [[Power Girl]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= Hughes, Adam|inker= Hughes, Adam|story= The Origin of Power Girl|title= 52|issue= #36|date= March 2007 [January 10, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 37: [[Firestorm (comics)|Firestorm the Nuclear Man]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Jamal Igle|Igle, Jamal]]|inker= Champagne, Keith|story= The Origin of Firestorm the Nuclear Man|title= 52|issue= #37|date= March 2007 [January 17, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 38: The [[Red Tornado]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Phil Jimenez|Jimenez, Phil]]|inker= Lanning, Andy|story= The Origin of Red Tornado|title= 52|issue= #38|date= March 2007 [January 24, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 39: [[Mister Terrific (Michael Holt)|Mr. Terrific]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Ethan Van Sciver|Van Sciver, Ethan]]|inker= Van Sciver, Ethan|story= The Origin of Mr. Terrific|title= 52|issue= #39|date= March 2007 [January 31, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 41: [[Starfire (Koriand'r)|Starfire]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Joe Benitez|Benitez, Joe]]|inker= Benitez, Joe|story= The Origin of Starfire|title= 52|issue= #41|date= April 2007 [February 14, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 42: The [[Green Arrow]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Scott McDaniel|McDaniel, Scott]]|inker= Owens, Andy|story= The Origin of Green Arrow|title= 52|issue= #42|date=April 2007 [February 21, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 43: [[Plastic Man]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= Van Sciver, Ethan|inker= Van Sciver, Ethan|story= The Origin of Plastic Man|title= 52|issue= #43|date= April 2007 [February 28, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 46: [[Batman]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Andy Kubert|Kubert, Andy]]|inker= Kubert, Andy|story= The Origin of Batman|title= 52|issue= #46|date= May 2007 [March 21, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 47: The [[Teen Titans]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Karl Kerschl|Kerschl, Karl]]|inker= Kerschl, Karl|story= The Origin of the Teen Titans|title= 52|issue= #47|date= May 2007 [March 28, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 48: The [[Birds of Prey (comic book)|Birds of Prey]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Nicola Scott|Scott, Nicola]]|inker= [[Doug Hazlewood|Hazlewood, Doug]]|story= The Origin of the Birds of Prey|title= 52|issue= #48|date= June 2007 [April 7, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 49: The [[Justice Society of America]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Don Kramer|Kramer, Don]]|inker= [[Michael Bair|Bair, Michael]]|story= The Origin of the Justice Society of America|title= 52|issue= #49|date= June 2007 [April 11, 2007]}}</ref>\n*Week 51: The [[Justice League|Justice League of America]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= Reis, Ivan|inker= Albert, Oclair|story= The Origin of the Justice League of America|title= 52|issue= #51|date= June 2007 [April 25, 2007]}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==''Secret Origins of Super-Villains''==\nBeginning with #37, each issue of ''[[Countdown to Final Crisis|Countdown]]'' featured the origins of a supervillain, written by [[Scott Beatty]]. The origins are:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* #37: [[Poison Ivy (character)|Poison Ivy]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= [[Scott Beatty|Beatty, Scott]]|penciller= [[St\u00e9phane Roux (comics)|Roux, St\u00e9phane]]|inker= Roux, St\u00e9phane|story= The Origin of Poison Ivy|title= [[Countdown to Final Crisis|Countdown]]|issue= #37|date= October 2007 [August 15, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #36: [[Deathstroke|Deathstroke the Terminator]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Tony Daniel|Daniel, Tony]]|inker= Glapion, Jon|story= The Origin of Deathstroke the Terminator|title= Countdown|issue= #36|date= October 2007 [August 22, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #35: [[Parallax (comics)|Parallax]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Reis, Ivan|inker= Albert, Oclair|story= The Origin of Parallax|title= Countdown|issue= #35|date= October 2007 [August 29, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #34: [[Lex Luthor]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Andy Clarke (comics)|Clarke, Andy]]|inker= Clarke, Andy|story= The Origin of Lex Luthor|title= Countdown|issue= #34|date= November 2007 [September 5, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #33: The [[Riddler]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Kramer, Don|inker= Kramer, Don|story= The Origin of the Riddler|title= Countdown|issue= #33|date= November 2007 [September 12, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #32: [[Eclipso]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Phil Winslade|Winslade, Phil]]|inker= Winslade, Phil|story= The Origin of Eclipso|title= Countdown|issue= #32|date= November 2007 [September 19, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #31: The [[Joker (character)|Joker]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Bolland, Brian|inker= Bolland, Brian|story= The Origin of the Joker|title= Countdown|issue= #31|date= November 2007 [September 26, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #30: [[General Zod]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Gary Frank|Frank, Gary]]|inker= Sibal, Jonathan|story= The Origin of General Zod|title= Countdown|issue= #30|date= December 2007 [October 3, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #29: The [[Penguin (character)|Penguin]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= McDaniel. Scott|inker= Owens, Andy|story= The Origin of the Penguin|title= Countdown|issue= #29|date= December 2007 [October 10, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #28: The [[Trickster (comics)|Trickster]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Van Sciver, Ethan|inker= Van Sciver, Ethan|story= The Origin of the Trickster|title= Countdown|issue= #28|date= December 2007 [October 17, 2007]}}</ref> and the [[Pied Piper (comics)|Pied Piper]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Van Sciver, Ethan|inker= Van Sciver, Ethan|story= The Origin of the Pied Piper|title= Countdown|issue= #28|date= December 2007 [October 17, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #27: [[Two-Face]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Mark Chiarello|Chiarello, Mark]]|inker= Chiarello, Mark|story= The Origin of Two-Face|title= Countdown|issue= #27|date= December 2007 [October 24, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #25: [[Killer Frost]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Igle, Jamal|inker= Champagne, Keith|story= The Origin of Killer Frost|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #25|date= January 2008 [November 7, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #24: [[Desaad|DeSaad]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Walt Simonson|Simonson, Walt]]|inker= Simonson, Walt|story= The Origin of Desaad|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #24|date= January 2008 [November 14, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #23: [[Mister Mxyzptlk|Mr. Mxyzptlk]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Kyle Baker|Baker, Kyle]]|inker= Baker, Kyle|story= The Origin of Mr. Mxyzptlk|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #23|date= January 2008 [November 21, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #22: [[Deadshot]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Williams II, Freddie|inker= Williams II, Freddie|story= The Origin of Deadshot|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #22|date= January 2008 [November 28, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #21: [[Granny Goodness]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Bogdanove, Jon|inker= Bogdanove, Jon|story= The Origin of Granny Goodness|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #21|date= February 2008 [December 5, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #20: [[Mister Mind and the Monster Society of Evil|Mr. Mind]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Bennett, Joe|inker= Jadson, Jack|story= The Origin of Mr. Mind|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #20|date= February 2008 [December 12, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #19: The [[Scarecrow (DC Comics)|Scarecrow]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Kelley Jones|Jones, Kelley]]|inker= Jones, Kelley|story= The Origin of the Scarecrow|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #19|date= February 2008 [December 19, 2007]}}</ref>\n{{col-2}} \n* #18: [[Doctor Light (Arthur Light)|Dr. Light]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Howard Porter (artist)|Porter, Howard]]|inker= Porter, Howard|story= The Origin of Dr. Light|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #18|date= February 2008 [December 26, 2007]}}</ref>\n* #17: The [[Monarch (comics)|Monarch]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Scott Kolins|Kolins, Scott]]|inker= Kolins, Scott|story= The Origin of Monarch|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #17|date= March 2008 [January 2, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #16: [[Sinestro]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Fernando Pasarin|Pasarin, Fernando]]|inker= Pasarin, Fernando|story= The Origin of Sinestro|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #16|date= March 2008 [January 9, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #15: [[Doomsday (comics)|Doomsday]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Bogdanove, Jon|inker= Bogdanove, Jon|story= The Origin of Doomsday|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #15|date= March 2008 [January 16, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #14: [[Gorilla Grodd]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Arthur Adams (comics)|Adams, Arthur]]|inker= Adams, Arthur|story= The Origin of Gorilla Grodd|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #14|date= March 2008 [January 23, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #13: The [[Hank Henshaw|Cyborg Superman]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Reis, Ivan |inker= Albert, Oclair|story= The Origin of Cyborg|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #13|date= March 2008 [January 30, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #12: [[Circe (comics)|Circe]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Aaron Lopresti|Lopresti, Aaron]]|inker= Lopresti, Aaron|story= The Origin of Circe|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #12|date= April 2008 [February 6, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #11: [[Solomon Grundy (comics)|Solomon Grundy]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Mandrake, Tom|inker= Mandrake, Tom|story= The Origin of Solomon Grundy|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #11|date= April 2008 [February 13, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #10: [[Harley Quinn]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Bruce Timm|Timm, Bruce]]|inker= Timm, Bruce|story= The Origin of Harley Quinn|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #10|date= April 2008 [February 20, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #9: [[Black Manta]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Mike Norton|Norton, Mike]]|inker= Ramos, Rodney|story= The Origin of Black Manta|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #9|date= April 2008 [February 27, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #8: [[Bizarro]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Doug Mahnke|Mahnke, Doug]]|inker= Mahnke, Doug|story= This Am Unsecret Origin of Bizarro!|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #8|date= May 2008 [March 5, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #7: [[Bane (comics)|Bane]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Graham Nolan|Nolan, Graham]]|inker= Nolan, Graham|story= The Origin of Bane|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #7|date= May 2008 [March 12, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #6: [[Felix Faust]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Saiz, Jesus|inker= Saiz, Jesus|story= The Origin of Felix Faust|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #6|date= May 2008 [March 19, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #5: [[Mr. Freeze]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Tom Derenick|Derenick, Tom]]|inker= Faucher, Wayne|story= The Origin of Mr. Freeze|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #5|date= May 2008 [March 26, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #4: [[Ra's al Ghul]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Cliff Chiang|Chiang, Cliff]]|inker= Chiang, Cliff|story= The Origin of Ra's al Ghul|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #4|date= June 2008 [April 2, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #3: [[Amazo]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= Mahnke, Doug|inker= Mahnke, Doug|story= The Origin of Amazo|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #3|date= June 2008 [April 9, 2008]}}</ref>\n* #2: [[Darkseid]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Beatty, Scott|penciller= [[Ryan Sook|Sook, Ryan]]|inker= Sook, Ryan|story= The Origin of Darkseid|title= Countdown to Final Crisis|issue= #2|date= June 2008 [April 16, 2008]}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Secret Files and Origins]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id= 547|title= ''Secret Origins'' one-shot}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id= 548|title= ''Secret Origins''}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id= 549|title= ''Secret Origins'' vol. 2}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id= 43679|title= ''Secret Origins'' vol. 3}}\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/series.php?seriesid=1763 ''Secret Origins''], [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/series.php?seriesid=1764 ''Secret Origins'' vol. 2], and [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/series.php?seriesid=14502 ''Secret Origins'' vol. 3] at Mike's Amazing World of Comics\n\n{{The New 52|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1973 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:1974 comics endings]]\n[[Category:1986 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:1990 comics endings]]\n[[Category:2014 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 comics endings]]\n[[Category:Comics anthologies]]\n[[Category:Comics by Alan Moore]]\n[[Category:Comics by Dennis O'Neil]]\n[[Category:Comics by Gerry Conway]]\n[[Category:Comics by J. M. DeMatteis]]\n[[Category:Comics by Len Wein]]\n[[Category:Comics by Mark Waid]]\n[[Category:Comics by Marv Wolfman]]\n[[Category:Comics by Michael Fleisher]]\n[[Category:Comics by Neil Gaiman]]\n[[Category:Comics by Paul Kupperberg]]\n[[Category:Comics by Paul Levitz]]\n[[Category:Comics by Roy Thomas]]\n[[Category:Comics by Steve Englehart]]\n[[Category:DC Comics one-shots]]\n[[Category:DC Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Defunct American comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title               = Secret Origins\n|image               = Secret Origins TPB.jpg\n|caption             = [[Brian Bolland]]'s cover to the 1989 ''Secret Origins'' collection\n|schedule            = Monthly\n|limited             =\n|ongoing             = y\n|1shot               =\n|Superhero           = y\n|publisher           = [[DC Comics]]\n|date                = '''One-shot:'''<br>Summer 1961<br>'''Vol. 1'''<br>February\u2013March 1973; October\u2013November 1974<br>'''Vol. 2''':<br>April 1986 \u2013 August 1990<br>'''Vol. 3''':<br>June 2014 \u2013 May 2015\n|issues              = '''One-shot:''' 1<br>'''Vol. 1''': 7<br>'''Vol. 2''': 50, plus 3 ''Annual''s and 1 ''Special''<br>'''Vol. 3''': 11  \n|main_char_team      =\n|writers             =\n|artists             =\n|pencillers          =\n|inkers              =\n|letterers           =\n|colorists           =\n|editors             = [[Roy Thomas]]<br>[[Mark Waid]]\n|creative_team_month =\n|creative_team_year  =\n|creators            =\n|TPB                 = Secret Origins\n|ISBN                = 0-930289-50-1\n|TPB#                =\n|ISBN#               =\n|subcat              = DC Comics\n|altcat              =\n|sort                = Secret Origins\n|addpubcat#          =\n|nonUS               =\n}}\n'''''Secret Origins''''' is the title of several [[comic book]] series published by [[DC Comics]] which featured the [[Origin story|origin stories]] of the publisher's various characters.\n\n==Publication history==\n''Secret Origins'' was first published as a [[One-shot (comics)|one-shot]] in 1961 and contained only reprinted material.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=1471|title= ''Secret Origins'' one-shot}}</ref> The title became an ongoing reprint series in February&ndash;March 1973 which ran for seven issues and ended in October\u2013November 1974.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=2104|title= ''Secret Origins''}}</ref> The title was used on various compilations of origin stories, including ''[[Limited Collectors' Edition]]'' #C-39: ''Secret Origins Super-Villains'' (October\u2013November 1975)<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 68954|title= ''Limited Collectors' Edition'' #C-39}}</ref> and #C-45: ''More Secret Origins Super-Villains'' (June\u2013July 1976)<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 68959|title= ''Limited Collectors' Edition'' #C-45}}</ref> as well as ''[[DC Special Series]]'' #10 (1978)<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 31908|title= ''DC Special Series'' #10}}</ref> and #19 (Fall 1979).<ref>{{Gcdb issue|id= 33806|title= ''DC Special Series'' #19}}</ref> Its most well-known incarnation was a 50-issue series that ran from April 1986 to August 1990,<ref>{{gcdb series|id=3166|title= ''Secret Origins'' vol. 2}}</ref> plus three ''Annual''s<ref>{{gcdb series|id=3377|title= ''Secret Origins Annual''}}</ref> and one ''Special''.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=3819|title= ''Secret Origins Special''}}</ref> Typically, an issue would clarify the [[Crisis on Infinite Earths|Post-''Crisis'']] origins of a number of characters,<ref>{{cite book|last=Manning|first= Matthew K.|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1980s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year= 2010|location= London, United Kingdom|isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9|page= 218|quote = The heroes of the DC Universe got a little more exposed thanks to the new ongoing effort ''Secret Origins'', a title offering new interpretations to the backgrounds of some of comics' biggest icons.}}</ref> usually two as most of the issues were double-sized, i.e. 48 pages. [[Roy Thomas]] was the initial writer/editorial consultant on the series; later issues were overseen by [[Mark Waid]]. Two more specials followed in 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{gcdb series|id=5994|title= ''Secret Origins 80-Page Giant''}} and {{gcdb series|id=10200|title= ''Secret Origins of Super-Villains 80-Page Giant''}}</ref> In 2004, it returned to the all-reprint format with a ''Weird Secret Origins'' special featuring [[Doctor Fate]], the [[Spectre (DC Comics character)|Spectre]], [[Animal Man]], the [[Enchantress (DC Comics)|Enchantress]], [[Metamorpho]], [[Congorilla]], [[El Diablo (comics)|El Diablo]], and the [[Bizarro World]].\n\nA new monthly incarnation focusing on characters in ''[[The New 52]]'', launched in April 2014 with a June 2014 [[cover date]]. The first issue featured the origins of [[Superman]], [[Supergirl]] and the [[Dick Grayson]] version of [[Robin (character)|Robin]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=50240|title= Exclusive: DC's ''Secret Origins'' & Tomasi's ''Batman Vs. Bane'' To Debut in April|first= Steve|last= Sunu|date= January 13, 2014|website= [[Comic Book Resources]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140712085611/http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=50240|archivedate= July 12, 2014|url-status= live}} Archive requires scrolldown</ref> This series was cancelled as of issue #11 (May 2015)<ref>{{gcdb series|id= 80309|title= ''Secret Origins'' vol. 3}}</ref> on sale in March 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-12/16/dc-cancellations|title= DC Comics cancels half its line from March 2015|first= Matt|last= Kamen|date= December 16, 2014|magazine= [[Wired UK]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150908083204/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-12/16/dc-cancellations|archivedate= September 8, 2015|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Characters featured in the 1986\u20131990 series==\n* '''#1''' (April 1986): The [[Golden Age of Comics|Golden Age]] [[Superman (Earth-Two)|Superman]]; this was intended as a tribute to the original version of the character, as the latter-day version of Superman was being concurrently introduced by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] in the ''[[The Man of Steel (comic book)|Man Of Steel]]'' miniseries; art by Golden Age Superman artist [[Wayne Boring]] and [[Jerry Ordway]].\n* '''#2''' (May 1986): The [[Blue Beetle]], both the Dan Garrett and Ted Kord versions; art by [[Gil Kane]].\n* '''#3''' (June 1986): [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Captain Marvel]] credited by the ''Shazam!'' title; a retelling of the story from ''WHIZ Comics'' #2, albeit updated to modern day.  Much of this was changed in the ''[[Legends (comics)|Legends]]'' crossover, Thomas himself would [[Retroactive continuity|retcon]] this some months later in ''[[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)#Captain Marvel in the late 1980s|SHAZAM! The New Beginning]]'', and all of which was changed again by Jerry Ordway in his [[graphic novel]] ''[[The Power of Shazam!]]''.\n* '''#4''' (July 1986): [[Firestorm (comics)|Firestorm]] (Ronnie Raymond).\n* '''#5''' (August 1986): the original [[Crimson Avenger (Lee Travis)|Crimson Avenger]]; art by [[Gene Colan]].\n* '''#6''' (September 1986): [[Halo (comics)|Halo]] of the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]]; the Golden Age [[Batman (Earth-Two)|Batman]]. This was the first double-sized issue.\n* '''#7''' (October 1986): [[Guy Gardner (comics)|Guy Gardner]]; the Golden Age [[Sandman (Wesley Dodds)|Sandman]]\n* '''#8''' (November 1986): [[Shadow Lass]]; [[Doll Man]].\n* '''#9''' (December 1986): The original [[Star-Spangled Kid]] (Skyman) and [[Stripesy]]; the Golden Age [[Flash (Jay Garrick)|Flash]].\n* '''#10''' (January 1987): The [[Phantom Stranger]]. This was a ''[[Legends (comics)|Legends]]'' tie-in that related four possible origins for the character; one by Mike Barr and [[Jim Aparo]] was a variation on the [[Wandering Jew]] myth, while another by [[Alan Moore]] and [[Joe Orlando]] postulated that the Stranger was a fallen angel.\n* '''#11''' (February 1987): the Golden Age [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]]; [[Power Girl]]. Both stories presented have since been retconned, with Power Girl's backstory having been redefined by [[Geoff Johns]] in the pages of ''JSA Classified'', which served as part of the buildup to ''[[Infinite Crisis]]''.\n* '''#12''' (March 1987): The [[Challengers of the Unknown]]; [[Fury (DC Comics)|Fury]].\n* '''#13''' (April 1987): [[Dick Grayson|Nightwing]] (art by [[Erik Larsen]]); [[Johnny Thunder#Original version|Johnny Thunder and his Thunderbolt]]; the Whip.\n* '''#14''' (May 1987): [[Suicide Squad]]. Another ''Legends'' tie-in, it served as a prequel to the later series and was written by that series' writer, [[John Ostrander]].\n* '''#15''' (June 1987): The [[Spectre (DC Comics character)|Spectre]]; [[Deadman (DC Comics)|Deadman]].\n* '''#16''' (July 1987): [[Hourman]]; the [[Warlord (DC Comics)|Warlord]]; [['Mazing Man]].\n* '''#17''' (August 1987): [[Adam Strange]]; [[Doctor Occult]].\n* '''#18''' (September 1987): The Golden Age Green Lantern ([[Alan Scott]]); the [[Creeper (comics)|Creeper]].\n* '''#19''' (October 1987): [[Uncle Sam (comics)|Uncle Sam]]; the [[Guardian (DC Comics)|Guardian]].\n* '''#20''' (November 1987): [[Barbara Gordon|Batgirl]]; [[Doctor Mid-Nite]].\n* '''#21''' (December 1987): [[Jonah Hex]]; the [[Black Condor]].\n* '''#22''' (January 1988): the [[Manhunters (DC Comics)|Manhunters]]. This was a tie-in with ''[[Millennium (comics)|Millennium]]'' as was the subsequent issue, and aligned the various histories of the characters with the [[Manhunter (comics)|Manhunter]] name together.\n* '''#23''' (February 1988): the [[Guardians of the Universe]] written by [[Todd Klein]]; the [[Floronic Man]] written by [[Rick Veitch]].\n* '''#24''' (March 1988): [[Doctor Fate]]; [[Blue Devil (DC Comics)|Blue Devil]]. Mark Waid became editor beginning with this issue.\n* '''#25''' (April 1988): The [[Legion of Super-Heroes]] (now apocryphal); the Golden Age [[Atom (Al Pratt)|Atom]].\n* '''#26''' (May 1988): [[Black Lightning]]; [[Miss America (DC Comics)|Miss America]].\n* '''#27''' (June 1988): [[Zatanna]], her father [[Zatara]], and [[Doctor Mist]].\n* '''#28''' (July 1988): [[Midnight (comics)|Midnight]] art by Gil Kane; [[Nightshade (DC Comics)|Nightshade]] art by [[Rob Liefeld]].  Nightshade's origin doubled as an introduction/backdrop to a three-issue ''Suicide Squad'' story arc where she returned to her place of origin to save her brother.\n* '''#29''' (August 1988): The [[Atom (Ray Palmer)|Atom]]; the [[Red Tornado (Golden Age)|Red Tornado]] (Ma Hunkel; this was [[Sheldon Mayer]]'s last comic book story); [[Tex Thompson|Mr. America]] (a.k.a. the Americommando).\n* '''#30''' (September 1988): [[Plastic Man]]; the [[Elongated Man]].\n* '''#31''' (October 1988): The [[Justice Society of America]]. A full-length story, and Roy Thomas' last contribution to the series, excluding the Grim Ghost story in #42.\n* '''#32''' (November 1988): The [[Justice League|Justice League of America]]. In a full-length story by [[Keith Giffen]] and [[Peter David]], the Justice League is formed by [[Green Lantern]] ([[Hal Jordan]]), the [[Flash (Barry Allen)]], [[Aquaman]], the Martian Manhunter and the Black Canary. Superman and Batman were not founding members, and [[Wonder Woman]]'s revised continuity precluded her from the same. The events depicted were later expanded upon in ''JLA: Year One'' and ''JLA: Incarnations''.\n* '''#33''' (December 1988): [[Fire (DC Comics)|Fire]], [[Ice (comics)|Ice]] and [[Mister Miracle]]. This and the subsequent two issues dealt with the members of Justice League International.\n* '''#34''' (Winter 1988): [[Captain Atom]], [[G'nort]] and [[Rocket Red]].\n* '''#35''' (Holiday 1988): [[Booster Gold]], [[Maxwell Lord]], and the [[Martian Manhunter]] rendered apocryphal by events and revelations in J'onn J'onnz' later solo series.\n* '''#36''' (January 1989): Green Lantern ([[Hal Jordan]]) story by [[Christopher Priest (comics)|Jim Owsley]]; [[Poison Ivy (character)|Poison Ivy]] story by [[Neil Gaiman]].\n* '''#37''' (February 1989): The [[Legion of Substitute Heroes]]; the original [[Doctor Light (Arthur Light)|Doctor Light]].\n* '''#38''' (March 1989): The [[Green Arrow]] and [[Roy Harper (comics)|Speedy]].\n* '''#39''' (April 1989): [[Animal Man]] story by [[Grant Morrison]]; the [[Man-Bat]].\n* '''#40''' (May 1989): The [[Gorillas in comics|all-gorilla]] issue, spotlighting [[Congorilla]], [[Detective Chimp]], and [[Gorilla Grodd]].\n* '''#41''' (June 1989): The [[Rogues (comics)|Flash's Rogues Gallery]] - the [[Weather Wizard]], [[Heat Wave (comics)|Heat Wave]], the [[Trickster (comics)|Trickster]], the [[Pied Piper (comics)|Pied Piper]], [[Captain Boomerang]], and [[Captain Cold]].\n* '''#42''' (July 1989): [[Phantom Girl]]; the [[Gay Ghost]]/Grim Ghost.\n* '''#43''' (August 1989): The original [[Hawk and Dove]]; [[Cave Carson]]; [[Chris KL-99]].\n* '''#44''' (September 1989): [[Clayface]] I, II, III and IV. This issue gave background information for a story arc that appeared in ''[[Detective Comics]]'' #604-607 entitled ''The Mud Pack''.\n* '''#45''' (October 1989): [[Blackhawk (DC Comics)|Blackhawk]]; [[El Diablo (comics)|El Diablo]].\n* '''#46''' (December 1989): The headquarters of the Silver Age Justice League of America (story by Grant Morrison), the New Titans' [[Titans Tower]], and the 'rocketship clubhouse' of the Legion of Super Heroes. Arm Fall Off Boy makes his first appearance.\n* '''#47''' (February 1990): Deceased Legionnaires [[Ferro Lad]], [[Karate Kid (comics)|Karate Kid]] and [[Chemical King]].\n* '''#48''' (April 1990): [[Ambush Bug]], [[Stanley and His Monster]], [[Rex the Wonder Dog]], and the [[Trigger Twins]].\n* '''#49''' (June 1990): [[Bouncing Boy]], the [[Newsboy Legion]], and the [[Silent Knight]].\n* '''#50''' (August 1990): a 96-page last issue. This consisted of a [[prose]] retelling of [[Robin (character)|Dick Grayson]]'s first encounter with Batman by [[Dennis O'Neil]] and [[George P\u00e9rez]]; the first meeting of the Golden and Silver Age [[Flash (comics)|Flash]]es story by Grant Morrison; how [[Johnny Thunder#Western version|Johnny Thunder (the western hero)]] came to be; the definitive history of the [[Black Canary]]; and the stories behind the [[Dolphin (comics)|Dolphin]] and the [[Space Museum (comics)|Space Museum]].\n\n===''Annual''s and ''Special''s===\n* '''''Annual'' #1''' (1987): the [[Doom Patrol]] art by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]]; [[Captain Comet]].\n* '''''Annual'' #2''' (1988): The second and third Flashes ([[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen]] and [[Wally West]]).\n* '''''Annual'' #3''' (1989): the [[Teen Titans]]. This was an anniversary tribute with contributions from [[George P\u00e9rez]], [[Tom Grummett]], [[Irv Novick]], [[Dave Cockrum]], [[Kevin Maguire (artist)|Kevin Maguire]] and [[Colleen Doran]]. It also included five pages of ''[[Who's Who in the DC Universe|Who's Who]]'' entries on [[Bette Kane|Flamebird]], the [[Golden Eagle (comics)|Golden Eagle]], the [[Bumblebee (comics)|Bumblebee]], the [[Mal Duncan|Herald]], the Antithesis and the [[Mister Twister (comics)|Gargoyle]].\n* '''''Special'' #1''' (1989): the [[Penguin (character)|Penguin]] by [[Alan Grant (writer)|Alan Grant]] and [[Sam Kieth]], the [[Riddler]] by Neil Gaiman, [[Matt Wagner]] and [[Bernie Mireault]], and [[Two-Face]] by [[Mark Verheiden]] and [[Pat Broderick]].\n\nAdditionally, there was a belated ''Secret Origins 80-Page Giant'' issued in 1998 ({{ISBN|1-56389-440-8}}), that focused on the members of [[Young Justice]].\n\n==Collected edition==\nSome issues of the second series were collected in a [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]] along with other material and some original work in 1989 called ''Secret Origins'', but the official title, as stated in the book's [[Indicia (publishing)|indicia]], is given as ''Secret Origins of The World's Greatest Super-Heroes'' ({{ISBN|0930289501}}). The focus was on DC's major characters: origin of the Justice League of America (from #32), the Flash (Barry Allen, from ''Secret Origins Annual'' #2); Green Lantern (Hal Jordan, from #36); J'onn J'onnz, the Martian Manhunter (from #35); and Superman (from ''The Man of Steel'' #6). There was also an all-new retelling of Batman's origins, ''[[The Man Who Falls|Batman: The Man Who Falls]]'', by Dennis O'Neil and [[Dick Giordano]]; this story later served as a cited inspiration for the [[2005 in film|2005 film]] ''[[Batman Begins]]''.<ref name=\"genesis\">{{cite video | people=[[Dan DiDio|DiDio, Dan]] (Vice President of DC Comics), [[David S. Goyer|Goyer, David S.]] (Co-writer), [[Paul Levitz|Levitz, Paul]] (President - [[DC Comics]]), [[Christopher Nolan|Nolan, Christopher]] (Director), Schreck, Bob (Batman Editor - DC Comics)|date=2006|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0485650/|title=Genesis of the Bat | medium=DVD featurette}}</ref>\n\n==Characters featured in the 2014\u201315 series==\n \n* '''#1''' (June 2014): [[Superman]], [[Robin (character)|Robin]] ([[Dick Grayson]]), [[Supergirl]]\n* '''#2''' (July 2014): [[Batman]], [[Aquaman]], [[Starfire (Koriand'r)|Starfire]]\n* '''#3''' (August 2014): [[Green Lantern]] ([[Hal Jordan]]), [[Batwoman|Batwoman (Kate Kane)]], [[Red Robin (comics)|Red Robin]] ([[Tim Drake]])\n* '''#4''' (September 2014): [[Harley Quinn]], the [[Green Arrow]], [[Damian Wayne]]\n* '''#5''' (October 2014): [[Cyborg (comics)|Cyborg]], the [[Red Hood]] ([[Jason Todd]]), [[Mera (comics)|Mera]]\n* '''#6''' (December 2014): [[Wonder Woman]], [[Deadman (DC Comics)|Deadman]], [[Sinestro]]\n* '''#7''' (January 2015): The [[Flash (comics)|Flash]], the [[Huntress (comics)|Huntress]], [[Superboy]]\n* '''#8''' (February 2015): [[Dick Grayson|Grayson]], [[Animal Man]], [[Katana (comics)|Katana]]\n* '''#9''' (March 2015): The [[Swamp Thing]], [[Power Girl]], [[Green Lantern]] ([[John Stewart (comics)|John Stewart]])\n* '''#10''' (April 2015): [[Batgirl]], [[Firestorm (comics)|Firestorm]], [[Poison Ivy (character)|Poison Ivy]]\n* '''#11''' (May 2015): The [[Black Canary]], [[Guy Gardner (comics)|Green Lantern (Guy Gardner)]], [[John Constantine]]\n\n===Collected editions 2014\u201315 series===\n* ''Secret Origins Volume 1'' - collects ''Secret Origins'' (vol. 3) #1-4 (Feb. 2015)\n* ''Secret Origins Volume 2'' - collects ''Secret Origins'' (vol. 3) #5-11 (Aug. 2015)\n\n==''Secret Origins of Super-Heroes''==\nDuring ''[[52 (comics)|52]]'', Weeks 12 through 51 featured two-page origins of various superheroes, written by [[Mark Waid]]. The origins featured were:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*Week 12: [[Wonder Woman]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= [[Mark Waid|Waid, Mark]]|penciller= [[Adam Hughes|Hughes, Adam]]|inker= Hughes, Adam|story= The Origin of Wonder Woman|title= [[52 (comics)|52]]|issue= #12|date= September 2006 [July 26, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 13: The [[Elongated Man]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Kevin Nowlan|Nowlan, Kevin]]|inker= Nowlan, Kevin|story= The Origin of Elongated Man|title= 52|issue= #13|date= October 2006 [August 2, 2006]}}</ref>\n*Week 14: [[Metamorpho]]<ref>{{cite comic| writer= Waid, Mark|penciller= [[Eric Powell (comics)|Powell, Eric]]|inker= Powell, Eric|story= The Origin of Meta